WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.470 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.470 --> 00:00:04.446 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.446 --> 00:00:07.410 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:09.647 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.647 --> 00:00:10.980 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Thank you so much.

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:13.760 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to 6.1200, 6.120.

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:15.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how you
want to pronounce it.

00:00:15.510 --> 00:00:16.190 align:middle line:90%
Anything goes.

00:00:16.190 --> 00:00:18.080 align:middle line:90%
Either way, welcome.

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:20.910 align:middle line:84%
Really looking forward to a
great semester with all of you.

00:00:20.910 --> 00:00:26.060 align:middle line:84%
So a couple salient points,
structure-wise, schedule-wise,

00:00:26.060 --> 00:00:29.520 align:middle line:84%
we have lectures on Tuesday,
Thursday, 2:30 to 4:00,

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:32.240 align:middle line:84%
which I suppose you know
if you're here in person.

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.430 align:middle line:84%
We have recitations on
Wednesdays and Fridays.

00:00:35.430 --> 00:00:37.530 align:middle line:84%
We do take attendance
at recitations.

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:38.820 align:middle line:90%
It's worth 10% of your grade.

00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:41.490 align:middle line:84%
So we highly recommend that
you go, both for your grade.

00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:43.520 align:middle line:84%
And also, it's some of
the most useful time

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:45.470 align:middle line:90%
that you'll have this semester.

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:47.240 align:middle line:84%
You'll be working
with your peers

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:49.260 align:middle line:84%
to solve problems
in small groups.

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:52.680 align:middle line:84%
You'll have a TA there to
offer advice and suggestions.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:57.030 align:middle line:84%
It's really valuable time,
and I highly recommend you go.

00:00:57.030 --> 00:01:00.630 align:middle line:84%
I guarantee you'll
get a lot out of it.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.879 align:middle line:84%
Since it's such a valuable time
and such a limited resource,

00:01:03.879 --> 00:01:04.379 align:middle line:90%
Just.

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:09.450 align:middle line:84%
Two hours per week, we have what
we call warmup problems, which

00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:13.860 align:middle line:84%
are just quick, multiple choice
problems right there on Canvas,

00:01:13.860 --> 00:01:17.460 align:middle line:84%
to get you thinking about the
lecture material a little bit.

00:01:17.460 --> 00:01:19.030 align:middle line:90%
They're not meant to be hard.

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:21.300 align:middle line:84%
They're not meant
to be stressful.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:23.970 align:middle line:84%
But we do want you to think
about the problems a little bit

00:01:23.970 --> 00:01:26.610 align:middle line:84%
and answer them and
get the answers right.

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:29.400 align:middle line:84%
Getting the answer right is
not as strenuous as it sounds.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:32.550 align:middle line:84%
Because you get infinite
retries and instant feedback up

00:01:32.550 --> 00:01:33.750 align:middle line:90%
until the deadline.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:35.680 align:middle line:84%
So as long as you
remember to do it,

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.040 align:middle line:90%
you're going to get full points.

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:41.608 align:middle line:84%
You could, if you want,
just option A, click.

00:01:41.608 --> 00:01:42.400 align:middle line:90%
Nope, that's wrong.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:43.228 align:middle line:90%
Option B, click.

00:01:43.228 --> 00:01:44.020 align:middle line:90%
Nope, that's wrong.

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:46.090 align:middle line:84%
Option C-- we don't
recommend that.

00:01:46.090 --> 00:01:48.930 align:middle line:84%
Ideally, it's in your
favor to actually think

00:01:48.930 --> 00:01:51.850 align:middle line:84%
about the problem a little bit,
might even be a little faster.

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:54.390 align:middle line:84%
But the point is
to be a reminder

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:56.520 align:middle line:84%
to think about the lecture
material a little bit

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:58.400 align:middle line:90%
before you come to recitation.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:00.878 align:middle line:84%
What we want to avoid is
everyone shows up to recitation

00:02:00.878 --> 00:02:02.670 align:middle line:84%
and says, wait, what
are we covering today?

00:02:02.670 --> 00:02:03.450 align:middle line:90%
I don't even know.

00:02:03.450 --> 00:02:04.710 align:middle line:90%
I wasn't able to go to lecture.

00:02:04.710 --> 00:02:05.960 align:middle line:90%
I don't know what was covered.

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:07.640 align:middle line:90%
Can someone fill me in?

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:11.700 align:middle line:84%
I would prefer that we do the
catching up before recitation.

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:13.618 align:middle line:84%
So by the time we
get there, we know

00:02:13.618 --> 00:02:14.910 align:middle line:90%
what we're going to talk about.

00:02:14.910 --> 00:02:16.590 align:middle line:84%
We can ask any
questions we have.

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:18.140 align:middle line:84%
We can start working
on the problems

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:22.100 align:middle line:84%
and use that time as
productively as possible.

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:23.850 align:middle line:84%
So that's recitations
and warmups.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:25.080 align:middle line:90%
We have problem sets.

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:28.140 align:middle line:84%
We'll have weekly problem
sets, due on Monday nights.

00:02:28.140 --> 00:02:31.100 align:middle line:84%
I hope everyone turned
it in yesterday.

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:32.670 align:middle line:90%
They'll be released on Tuesdays.

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:33.750 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I got a thumbs up.

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:37.040 align:middle line:90%
Where did you send that?

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:38.760 align:middle line:84%
We release problem
sets Tuesdays.

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:41.550 align:middle line:84%
They'll be due on
Monday nights, 11:59 PM,

00:02:41.550 --> 00:02:46.130 align:middle line:84%
so as Monday night
as we can get.

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:50.420 align:middle line:84%
And I want to say a few words
about these problem sets, about

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:52.410 align:middle line:84%
the structure and about
the collaboration.

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:53.550 align:middle line:90%
We want you to collaborate.

00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:55.140 align:middle line:84%
We want you to work
with your peers.

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:57.560 align:middle line:84%
We want you to get help
from us in office hours

00:02:57.560 --> 00:02:59.280 align:middle line:84%
and on Piazza and
things like that.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:02.010 align:middle line:84%
We want you to solve these
problem sets collaboratively,

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:04.910 align:middle line:90%
if you so choose.

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:07.140 align:middle line:84%
We are signed up
for pset partners.

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:10.520 align:middle line:84%
So once a week, shortly after
the problem sets go out,

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:12.680 align:middle line:84%
the pset partner
site will match you

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:16.183 align:middle line:84%
with other problem set solvers
that have similar schedules.

00:03:16.183 --> 00:03:17.850 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to
find a group that way,

00:03:17.850 --> 00:03:19.020 align:middle line:90%
you're more than welcome to.

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:21.980 align:middle line:84%
We'll set it to go off a
couple days after each problem

00:03:21.980 --> 00:03:22.800 align:middle line:90%
set releases.

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:24.360 align:middle line:84%
So just be sure to
sign up on time.

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:27.500 align:middle line:84%
If you miss the first round, you
can sign up in the second round.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:29.805 align:middle line:84%
Or you can come to office
hours and find friends there.

00:03:29.805 --> 00:03:31.430 align:middle line:84%
You can work with
friends at your dorm.

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:33.680 align:middle line:84%
However you want to find
partners, go ahead and do it,

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:34.580 align:middle line:90%
if you want.

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:37.250 align:middle line:84%
And we encourage you to solve
these problems correctly--

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:39.480 align:middle line:84%
or sorry, collaboratively--
also, correctly--

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:41.296 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:41.296 --> 00:03:43.970 align:middle line:90%
--not the worst Freudian slip.

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:45.840 align:middle line:84%
We encourage you to
solve collaboratively.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:46.735 align:middle line:90%
Figure things out.

00:03:46.735 --> 00:03:48.360 align:middle line:84%
Some of these problems
are challenging.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:52.110 align:middle line:84%
Some of them have tricks that
you might not see immediately,

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:54.650 align:middle line:84%
and you have to figure
out what's going on.

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:58.970 align:middle line:84%
However, there's a second step
to the problem set process

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:00.420 align:middle line:84%
that I want to
call attention to.

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:02.240 align:middle line:90%
And that's the writing step.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:05.070 align:middle line:84%
One of the main
goals of this course,

00:04:05.070 --> 00:04:06.960 align:middle line:84%
one of the main exports
for this course,

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:12.350 align:middle line:84%
is proof writing, the ability to
write precise, concise, correct

00:04:12.350 --> 00:04:14.310 align:middle line:90%
mathematical arguments.

00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:17.209 align:middle line:84%
And that is a skill that we will
be practicing and developing

00:04:17.209 --> 00:04:18.660 align:middle line:90%
all semester.

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And everyone has a
slightly different style.

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:23.930 align:middle line:84%
Everyone thinks about
these things differently.

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And the act of just constructing
a proof, even if it all

00:04:27.530 --> 00:04:30.680 align:middle line:84%
makes perfect sense in your
head, the act of translating

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:33.740 align:middle line:84%
that into a proof
on paper that's

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:37.070 align:middle line:84%
able to be read and consumed
and believed by others

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:39.270 align:middle line:90%
is its own special skill.

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:42.080 align:middle line:84%
And we want you to get
lots of practice with that,

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:44.880 align:middle line:84%
keyword being "you,"
not your group.

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:47.610 align:middle line:84%
So go ahead and solve the
problems collaboratively.

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:49.620 align:middle line:84%
Whatever notes you've
generated, that's fine.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:50.280 align:middle line:90%
Keep them.

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:51.430 align:middle line:90%
Study from them.

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:53.430 align:middle line:84%
But when you're going to
write your problem set,

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:57.500 align:middle line:84%
put those notes aside, please,
and piece things together

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:00.810 align:middle line:84%
yourself in your words,
showing your understanding.

00:05:00.810 --> 00:05:03.230 align:middle line:90%
So solve together, write alone.

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:05.550 align:middle line:84%
Just to emphasize
this one more time,

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:09.590 align:middle line:84%
the reason I'm spending all
this time belaboring this point

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:13.970 align:middle line:84%
is something I like to call the
P versus NP fallacy, which just

00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:16.220 align:middle line:84%
says that reading and
understanding someone else's

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:20.540 align:middle line:84%
proof is easier
than constructing

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:22.190 align:middle line:90%
that proof yourself.

00:05:22.190 --> 00:05:24.710 align:middle line:84%
And it's really tempting
to think that these two

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:25.910 align:middle line:90%
tasks are equivalent.

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.070 align:middle line:84%
When you're studying
for a test, you

00:05:28.070 --> 00:05:30.052 align:middle line:84%
read through our
problem set solutions,

00:05:30.052 --> 00:05:31.260 align:middle line:90%
like, yeah, that makes sense.

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:31.830 align:middle line:90%
That makes sense.

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:32.430 align:middle line:90%
That makes sense.

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:32.930 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:05:32.930 --> 00:05:33.920 align:middle line:90%
I'm convinced.

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:36.290 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't immediately
translate to,

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:39.920 align:middle line:84%
I therefore could have
put it together myself.

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.260 align:middle line:84%
So understanding a
proof and writing

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:43.680 align:middle line:90%
a proof-- two different skills.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:46.070 align:middle line:84%
We want you to get
practice with both.

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:48.590 align:middle line:84%
Any questions about
that, about the intent

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:51.870 align:middle line:90%
behind our collaboration policy?

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:54.210 align:middle line:90%
Awesome.

00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:55.590 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:58.030 align:middle line:84%
Late problem sets, last
thing I want to talk about,

00:05:58.030 --> 00:06:00.070 align:middle line:90%
we do accept late problem sets.

00:06:00.070 --> 00:06:03.060 align:middle line:84%
We accept very
late problem sets.

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:06.548 align:middle line:84%
So we put a lot of effort into
making these problem sets,

00:06:06.548 --> 00:06:08.340 align:middle line:84%
at least trying to make
these problem sets,

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:10.540 align:middle line:90%
both interesting and useful.

00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:12.540 align:middle line:84%
And so we want to
incentivize all of you

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:16.980 align:middle line:84%
to work the problem sets as
much as you can in as many ways

00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:20.310 align:middle line:84%
as you can, even if
that means it's late.

00:06:20.310 --> 00:06:21.810 align:middle line:84%
If the schedule
doesn't line up, you

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:23.227 align:middle line:84%
had to miss some
problem sets, We.

00:06:23.227 --> 00:06:26.740 align:middle line:84%
Want you to be able to catch
up by doing the problem sets.

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:30.840 align:middle line:84%
So we allow late problem
sets up to and including

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.420 align:middle line:90%
the last day of classes.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:36.267 align:middle line:84%
If you forget to do problem
set one, and you remember,

00:06:36.267 --> 00:06:38.100 align:middle line:84%
oh, in the last week,
maybe I should go back

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:40.695 align:middle line:90%
and solve those problems--

00:06:40.695 --> 00:06:42.570 align:middle line:84%
probably would have been
more useful to do it

00:06:42.570 --> 00:06:46.260 align:middle line:84%
before the first quiz, but
better late than never.

00:06:46.260 --> 00:06:48.210 align:middle line:84%
You can still turn in
that problem set late

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:49.870 align:middle line:90%
for half credit.

00:06:49.870 --> 00:06:52.540 align:middle line:84%
More precisely, our
late problem set

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:56.020 align:middle line:84%
policy is that for
the first 50 hours,

00:06:56.020 --> 00:06:57.850 align:middle line:84%
the late penalty
or the percentage

00:06:57.850 --> 00:06:59.980 align:middle line:84%
of points that you will
earn from your submission

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:03.490 align:middle line:84%
goes from 100%, if it's
on time, down to 50%,

00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:07.850 align:middle line:84%
if it's 50 hours late, and 1%
each hour for those first 50

00:07:07.850 --> 00:07:10.040 align:middle line:90%
hours, those first two-ish days.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:13.930 align:middle line:84%
And then after that, it stays
at 50 for the rest of term.

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:18.850 align:middle line:84%
That also means
that if it's 11:45,

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:21.530 align:middle line:84%
and you have one problem
left-- you know how to do it.

00:07:21.530 --> 00:07:24.260 align:middle line:84%
You just down to the
wire for writing it down.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:27.640 align:middle line:84%
Or you want to take another
hour or 30 minutes or something

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:29.330 align:middle line:90%
to think about that problem.

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:31.220 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead and be a little late.

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:32.428 align:middle line:90%
It's not a big deal.

00:07:32.428 --> 00:07:33.970 align:middle line:84%
If you're one hour
late, you're still

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:37.280 align:middle line:84%
going to get 99% of the points
that you would have otherwise.

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:39.700 align:middle line:84%
It's worth it to
take that extra time.

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:43.480 align:middle line:84%
It means that there
isn't a sharp cutoff

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:46.040 align:middle line:84%
between before the deadline
and after the deadline.

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:47.930 align:middle line:90%
It's not a big deal.

00:07:47.930 --> 00:07:49.050 align:middle line:90%
Don't worry about it.

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:51.540 align:middle line:84%
We want to reduce stress
for everyone involved.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:53.065 align:middle line:90%
Any questions about that?

00:07:53.065 --> 00:07:56.325 align:middle line:90%


00:07:56.325 --> 00:07:56.825 align:middle line:90%
Excellent.

00:07:56.825 --> 00:07:57.900 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.530 align:middle line:84%
Like I said, lots more details
there on the course information

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:04.400 align:middle line:90%
policies PDF on our Canvas site.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:07.970 align:middle line:84%
And with that, let's
talk about some math.

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:13.430 align:middle line:84%
So as I said earlier, one
of the main skills and tools

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:15.860 align:middle line:84%
that we want you to have,
coming out of this class,

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:19.190 align:middle line:84%
is the ability to write proofs,
and read proofs, and evaluate

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:20.270 align:middle line:90%
proofs.

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.700 align:middle line:84%
As one of my colleagues
says, this class

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:26.030 align:middle line:84%
could have been called Proofs,
Proofs, and More Proofs.

00:08:26.030 --> 00:08:27.900 align:middle line:84%
We're going to talk
about proofs a lot,

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:30.410 align:middle line:84%
especially today, where
we're going to start with,

00:08:30.410 --> 00:08:32.895 align:middle line:90%
what is a proof?

00:08:32.895 --> 00:08:35.520 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to write that down
because it's important enough.

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.610 align:middle line:90%
What is a proof?

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:42.827 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to give
a starting answer.

00:08:42.827 --> 00:08:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to elaborate
on this a little bit.

00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:48.390 align:middle line:90%
Here's a question and answer.

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:59.370 align:middle line:84%
It's a method of
ascertaining truth.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:01.910 align:middle line:84%
A proof is how you show
that something is true.

00:09:01.910 --> 00:09:04.860 align:middle line:90%


00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:07.140 align:middle line:84%
And we as a society
have lots and lots

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:10.470 align:middle line:84%
of methods for
determining what's true,

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:11.860 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to give you a couple.

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:19.860 align:middle line:84%
For example, we have
experiments, and observation,

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:21.900 align:middle line:90%
and the scientific method.

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:25.740 align:middle line:84%
That is how we determine what's
true in the physical sciences.

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:27.183 align:middle line:90%
We have sampling.

00:09:27.183 --> 00:09:30.300 align:middle line:90%


00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:32.680 align:middle line:84%
If you want to know who's
likely to win an election,

00:09:32.680 --> 00:09:35.520 align:middle line:84%
you pick a random
sample, and you ask

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.540 align:middle line:90%
who they're going to vote for.

00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:40.320 align:middle line:90%
And you generalize.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.110 align:middle line:90%
We have legal proceedings.

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:46.060 align:middle line:90%
You hold a trial--

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:48.520 align:middle line:90%
two different L's-- who knew?

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:51.370 align:middle line:84%
You hold a trial to
determine what happened

00:09:51.370 --> 00:09:52.880 align:middle line:90%
and who's culpable.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:56.410 align:middle line:84%
That is how we determine
truth in those cases.

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:57.650 align:middle line:90%
Who can give me some others?

00:09:57.650 --> 00:09:58.920 align:middle line:90%
How do we determine truth?

00:09:58.920 --> 00:10:05.290 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:06.520 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:09.710 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: The investigation,
like in detective movies.

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:14.410 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: All right, yeah
investigation, absolutely,

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:19.120 align:middle line:84%
investigation,
looking for evidence,

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:22.540 align:middle line:84%
looking for the most
likely explanation that

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:24.412 align:middle line:84%
fits the observation,
so actually,

00:10:24.412 --> 00:10:26.120 align:middle line:84%
pretty similar to some
of the other ones.

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:26.530 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:27.380 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Asking questions?

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:28.672 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Asking questions?

00:10:28.672 --> 00:10:29.410 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:33.450 align:middle line:90%


00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:33.950 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:10:33.950 --> 00:10:35.760 align:middle line:90%
Let me give you a couple more.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.390 align:middle line:90%


00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:41.650 align:middle line:90%
Authority.

00:10:41.650 --> 00:10:45.900 align:middle line:84%
If your professor says this is
true, then it's true, right?

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:48.792 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:48.792 --> 00:10:49.760 align:middle line:90%


00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:52.490 align:middle line:90%
Please don't do that.

00:10:52.490 --> 00:10:54.350 align:middle line:84%
We make mistakes all
the time, and we want

00:10:54.350 --> 00:10:56.630 align:middle line:90%
you to call us out on that.

00:10:56.630 --> 00:10:57.853 align:middle line:90%
We have religion.

00:10:57.853 --> 00:11:02.930 align:middle line:90%


00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:04.740 align:middle line:90%
This is what our religion says.

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:06.120 align:middle line:90%
This is what our deity says.

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:09.360 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, it is true, and it
is how I should live my life.

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:13.460 align:middle line:84%
These are the values
I should value.

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:15.436 align:middle line:90%
We have inner conviction.

00:11:15.436 --> 00:11:20.900 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:23.300 align:middle line:84%
I just feel like it
should be this way.

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:25.080 align:middle line:84%
Deep in my gut,
I know it's true.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.200 align:middle line:90%
It came to me in a dream.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:33.110 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, that is
how things work;

00:11:33.110 --> 00:11:36.537 align:middle line:84%
so lots of different ways
of determining truth,

00:11:36.537 --> 00:11:38.120 align:middle line:84%
lots of different
meanings of the word

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:41.080 align:middle line:90%
truth in those situations.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:44.200 align:middle line:84%
And as mathematicians, we
have our own procedures

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:46.330 align:middle line:90%
for determining truth.

00:11:46.330 --> 00:11:49.360 align:middle line:84%
And that is a
mathematical proof.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:12:02.080 align:middle line:84%
So definition, a
mathematical proof

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:20.284 align:middle line:84%
is a verification
of a proposition

00:12:20.284 --> 00:12:38.323 align:middle line:84%
by a chain of logical deductions
from a base set of axioms.

00:12:38.323 --> 00:12:42.590 align:middle line:90%


00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:44.540 align:middle line:84%
A mathematical proof
is a verification

00:12:44.540 --> 00:12:47.930 align:middle line:84%
of a proposition by a chain of
logical deductions from a base

00:12:47.930 --> 00:12:49.470 align:middle line:90%
set of axioms.

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:52.190 align:middle line:84%
And there are three terms
inside of that definition

00:12:52.190 --> 00:12:54.930 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to focus
on today and tomorrow.

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:56.660 align:middle line:84%
We'll break them
down one at a time

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:59.840 align:middle line:84%
and hopefully, make
this make more sense.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:02.340 align:middle line:90%
Let's start with proposition.

00:13:02.340 --> 00:13:03.586 align:middle line:90%
What is a proposition?

00:13:03.586 --> 00:13:07.730 align:middle line:90%


00:13:07.730 --> 00:13:25.925 align:middle line:84%
Definition-- a proposition is a
statement that is true or false.

00:13:25.925 --> 00:13:29.102 align:middle line:90%


00:13:29.102 --> 00:13:30.750 align:middle line:90%
Today is Tuesday.

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:33.050 align:middle line:90%
Proposition?

00:13:33.050 --> 00:13:34.760 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:36.800 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Oh,
that is true, yeah.

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:38.880 align:middle line:90%
Today is Thursday.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.067 align:middle line:90%
Proposition?

00:13:40.067 --> 00:13:40.650 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:41.470 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Yeah.

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:43.306 align:middle line:84%
It's false, but it's
still a proposition.

00:13:43.306 --> 00:13:47.610 align:middle line:90%


00:13:47.610 --> 00:13:49.440 align:middle line:90%
Let's see, examples--

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:52.290 align:middle line:90%
2 plus 3 equals 5.

00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:54.450 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, proposition.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:59.760 align:middle line:84%
2 plus 3 equals 4,
still a proposition.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:01.680 align:middle line:90%
Here's one.

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:07.410 align:middle line:84%
For all n in the
natural numbers,

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:11.540 align:middle line:84%
n squared plus n
plus 41 is prime.

00:14:11.540 --> 00:14:14.910 align:middle line:90%


00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:16.180 align:middle line:90%
This is new notation.

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:17.200 align:middle line:90%
Let's break it down.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:20.800 align:middle line:90%
This says, for all.

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:24.850 align:middle line:84%
So for every n that is
in the natural numbers,

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:28.140 align:middle line:84%
this, what's called,
blackboard bold capital N

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:39.910 align:middle line:84%
is the natural numbers, also
known as the set 0, 1, 2, 3

00:14:39.910 --> 00:14:40.900 align:middle line:90%
and all the way up.

00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:43.600 align:middle line:84%
It starts at 0, starts
counting upwards.

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:47.050 align:middle line:84%
Outside of this
class, you might see

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:51.610 align:middle line:84%
people trying to convince you
that 0 is not a natural number.

00:14:51.610 --> 00:14:53.050 align:middle line:90%
They're wrong.

00:14:53.050 --> 00:14:54.820 align:middle line:84%
At least for the
purposes of this class,

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:56.475 align:middle line:90%
0 is always a natural number.

00:14:56.475 --> 00:14:59.240 align:middle line:90%


00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:03.160 align:middle line:84%
So every natural number for
every natural number n, n

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:06.340 align:middle line:90%
squared plus n plus 41 is prime.

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:11.080 align:middle line:90%
Is this a proposition?

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:15.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's a statement where
it at least makes sense to ask,

00:15:15.190 --> 00:15:18.280 align:middle line:90%
is this true or false?

00:15:18.280 --> 00:15:20.660 align:middle line:84%
There's a related
concept, by the way.

00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:24.920 align:middle line:84%
So this thing in here, just n
squared plus n plus 41 is prime,

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:26.096 align:middle line:90%
is that a proposition?

00:15:26.096 --> 00:15:29.410 align:middle line:90%


00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:33.340 align:middle line:84%
Let me give an even
easier example.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:36.990 align:middle line:84%
Oh, my examples were
already on that board.

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:37.490 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:41.450 align:middle line:90%


00:15:41.450 --> 00:15:41.960 align:middle line:90%
Even

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:46.640 align:middle line:90%
Easier example, p is prime.

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:49.400 align:middle line:90%
Is that a proposition?

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:51.330 align:middle line:90%
I'm seeing some thumbs down.

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:52.770 align:middle line:90%
I'm seeing some thumbs down.

00:15:52.770 --> 00:15:57.920 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's not a proposition,
not a proposition.

00:15:57.920 --> 00:16:00.240 align:middle line:84%
Because it's
incomplete information.

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:01.980 align:middle line:90%
What p are we talking about?

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:05.870 align:middle line:84%
If you tell me a p is 7 prime,
that's a proposition; is

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:08.070 align:middle line:90%
12 prime, that's a proposition.

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:11.090 align:middle line:84%
So this is sort of a
proposition with a variable

00:16:11.090 --> 00:16:14.190 align:middle line:84%
that we need to fill in before
it becomes a proposition.

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:17.150 align:middle line:84%
This is what's
called a predicate.

00:16:17.150 --> 00:16:18.846 align:middle line:90%
This is a predicate.

00:16:18.846 --> 00:16:22.958 align:middle line:90%


00:16:22.958 --> 00:16:24.500 align:middle line:84%
And I was bringing
back the old board

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:26.116 align:middle line:84%
so I could write
down that definition.

00:16:26.116 --> 00:16:31.280 align:middle line:90%


00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:44.100 align:middle line:84%
A predicate is a
proposition whose truth

00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:47.776 align:middle line:90%
depends on variables.

00:16:47.776 --> 00:16:52.110 align:middle line:90%


00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:54.550 align:middle line:84%
So it's a parametrized
proposition.

00:16:54.550 --> 00:16:56.650 align:middle line:84%
Once you tell me what
the variables are,

00:16:56.650 --> 00:16:58.710 align:middle line:90%
then it's a proposition.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:03.006 align:middle line:84%
And we just saw an
example up here.

00:17:03.006 --> 00:17:05.339 align:middle line:84%
I hope no one's getting dizzy
from all the boards moving

00:17:05.339 --> 00:17:07.200 align:middle line:90%
around.

00:17:07.200 --> 00:17:11.790 align:middle line:84%
We just saw an example
here, where this inside is

00:17:11.790 --> 00:17:14.490 align:middle line:90%
a predicate that depends on n.

00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:18.780 align:middle line:84%
And this for all is able to take
that predicate depending on n

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:22.900 align:middle line:84%
and wrap it up into what
is now a proposition.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:25.349 align:middle line:84%
It says that this
predicate about n

00:17:25.349 --> 00:17:27.760 align:middle line:84%
needs to be true for
every natural number.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:29.110 align:middle line:90%
And now it's a proposition.

00:17:29.110 --> 00:17:32.410 align:middle line:90%
It's either true or false.

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:33.860 align:middle line:90%
Is it true or false?

00:17:33.860 --> 00:17:35.540 align:middle line:84%
Let's see if we
can figure it out.

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:36.950 align:middle line:90%
We know it's a proposition.

00:17:36.950 --> 00:17:37.790 align:middle line:90%
But is it true?

00:17:37.790 --> 00:17:39.760 align:middle line:90%
Is it false?

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:44.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's do the natural
thing and try some examples.

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:46.270 align:middle line:90%
OK, well, here's n.

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:49.460 align:middle line:90%
Here's n squared plus n plus 41.

00:17:49.460 --> 00:17:52.820 align:middle line:90%
Is it prime?

00:17:52.820 --> 00:17:53.320 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:55.850 align:middle line:84%
So natural numbers,
remember, start at 0.

00:17:55.850 --> 00:17:58.840 align:middle line:90%
So when n is 0, this is 41--

00:17:58.840 --> 00:18:00.790 align:middle line:90%
absolutely prime.

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:05.180 align:middle line:84%
When n is 1, this
is 43, still prime.

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:06.260 align:middle line:90%
Looking good so far.

00:18:06.260 --> 00:18:07.310 align:middle line:90%
How about 2?

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:11.710 align:middle line:90%
I think we get 47, also prime.

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:15.940 align:middle line:84%
And if you check 3, 4, 5, 6,
prime, prime, prime, prime.

00:18:15.940 --> 00:18:18.490 align:middle line:90%
It keeps being prime.

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:21.590 align:middle line:84%
What if we go all
the way up to 39?

00:18:21.590 --> 00:18:25.900 align:middle line:84%
We get 1,601, if my
notes are to be believed,

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:28.630 align:middle line:90%
which is also prime.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:31.650 align:middle line:84%
This is looking pretty
convincing, right?

00:18:31.650 --> 00:18:33.450 align:middle line:90%
There we go.

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:36.780 align:middle line:84%
And in some fields of study,
just doing a sufficient number

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:40.680 align:middle line:84%
of examples would be enough
evidence for it to be true,

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:43.450 align:middle line:84%
or effectively true,
or as good as true.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:45.550 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, for
us mathematicians,

00:18:45.550 --> 00:18:49.450 align:middle line:84%
if we say for all n,
we need all of the n.

00:18:49.450 --> 00:18:51.725 align:middle line:84%
Just these 40
examples isn't enough.

00:18:51.725 --> 00:18:55.260 align:middle line:90%


00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:59.430 align:middle line:84%
And of course, if
you go one more--

00:18:59.430 --> 00:19:00.820 align:middle line:90%
did I write this down?

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:02.790 align:middle line:90%
Oh, here.

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:04.660 align:middle line:90%
Let's jump to 41.

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:07.530 align:middle line:84%
41 looks a good
example because that's

00:19:07.530 --> 00:19:12.060 align:middle line:84%
going to be a multiple of 41,
multiple of 41, multiple of 41.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:21.420 align:middle line:84%
It turns out, what you get is
41 times 43, which is not prime.

00:19:21.420 --> 00:19:25.000 align:middle line:84%
And so we found an example
where this is not prime.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:31.040 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, this
proposition is false.

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:34.200 align:middle line:84%
If it's supposed to be true
for every natural number,

00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:35.990 align:middle line:84%
to disprove it,
all we need to find

00:19:35.990 --> 00:19:39.620 align:middle line:84%
is a single counterexample,
a single number n

00:19:39.620 --> 00:19:43.100 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't satisfy
the required conditions.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:45.020 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:45.620 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:48.020 align:middle line:84%
Turns out, if you
go to 40, I'm pretty

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:52.130 align:middle line:84%
sure you get 41 squared,
which is also not prime.

00:19:52.130 --> 00:19:55.490 align:middle line:84%
So 0 through 39
are really the most

00:19:55.490 --> 00:19:59.100 align:middle line:90%
you're going to get in that run.

00:19:59.100 --> 00:20:05.210 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at another
example of a fun proposition,

00:20:05.210 --> 00:20:07.890 align:middle line:84%
just to get more
familiar with this.

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:09.636 align:middle line:90%
Let's see Goldbach's Conjecture.

00:20:09.636 --> 00:20:19.250 align:middle line:90%


00:20:19.250 --> 00:20:22.370 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:33.730 align:middle line:84%
Every even number greater than
2 is the sum of two primes.

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:38.720 align:middle line:90%


00:20:38.720 --> 00:20:41.580 align:middle line:84%
Every even number greater than
2 is the sum of two primes.

00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:43.405 align:middle line:90%
For example, can we do 12?

00:20:43.405 --> 00:20:47.210 align:middle line:90%


00:20:47.210 --> 00:20:48.470 align:middle line:90%
Who can tell me?

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:49.050 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:49.330 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:50.080 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: 7 plus 5.

00:20:50.080 --> 00:20:51.500 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: 7
plus 5, excellent.

00:20:51.500 --> 00:20:55.800 align:middle line:84%
7 plus 5, prime plus prime,
so 12 is a sum of two primes.

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:58.850 align:middle line:84%
The claim is that every
even number starting at 4

00:20:58.850 --> 00:21:02.630 align:middle line:84%
can be written as the
sum of two primes.

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:05.240 align:middle line:84%
And it's called a
conjecture because we

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:08.030 align:middle line:90%
don't know if it's true.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:12.900 align:middle line:84%
I love, in math, and often,
especially in number theory,

00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:17.880 align:middle line:84%
you can state these very simply
stated conjectures, theorems,

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:22.680 align:middle line:84%
questions, that are just
beyond human understanding.

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:25.950 align:middle line:84%
They're beyond the scope of what
modern mathematical tools are

00:21:25.950 --> 00:21:27.820 align:middle line:90%
able to tackle.

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:29.850 align:middle line:84%
And it's really
pretty, that right here

00:21:29.850 --> 00:21:31.510 align:middle line:84%
is beyond the
cutting edge of math.

00:21:31.510 --> 00:21:37.110 align:middle line:84%
We've already gotten their first
lecture, yeah, really pretty

00:21:37.110 --> 00:21:37.990 align:middle line:90%
problem.

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, in, I think, 1995,
it was highlighted in The Globe

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:48.155 align:middle line:84%
as one of the biggest
unknown questions in math,

00:21:48.155 --> 00:21:52.170 align:middle line:84%
right here,
Goldbach's Conjecture.

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:57.540 align:middle line:84%
For example, 20 can be
expressed as 9 plus 11.

00:21:57.540 --> 00:21:59.105 align:middle line:90%
Oops, 9 isn't prime.

00:21:59.105 --> 00:22:04.180 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.180 --> 00:22:07.620 align:middle line:84%
So have we disproven
Goldbach's conjecture?

00:22:07.620 --> 00:22:08.280 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:08.920 align:middle line:90%
Why not?

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:09.992 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:22:09.992 --> 00:22:12.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's 17 plus 3.

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:19.450 align:middle line:84%
20 is 17 plus 3; so
really pretty question,

00:22:19.450 --> 00:22:21.600 align:middle line:84%
wish the reporting
had been better.

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:24.880 align:middle line:90%
But we can forgive them.

00:22:24.880 --> 00:22:27.820 align:middle line:84%
Are there any questions about
propositions and predicates

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:28.940 align:middle line:90%
so far?

00:22:28.940 --> 00:22:30.370 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:33.310 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: The p is prime,
which is not a proposition.

00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:37.660 align:middle line:84%
And define predicate
as a proposition?

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:39.920 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Yeah,
that's a very good point.

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:41.845 align:middle line:84%
That wording is
maybe not great--

00:22:41.845 --> 00:22:45.526 align:middle line:90%


00:22:45.526 --> 00:22:54.345 align:middle line:84%
is a proposition that depends
on variables except that--

00:22:54.345 --> 00:22:56.890 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:59.770 align:middle line:90%
it depends on variables.

00:22:59.770 --> 00:23:02.170 align:middle line:84%
It becomes a proposition
after you give values

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:03.290 align:middle line:90%
to the variables.

00:23:03.290 --> 00:23:06.165 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I agree we should fix
that for the next go around.

00:23:06.165 --> 00:23:08.800 align:middle line:90%


00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:10.150 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:23:10.150 --> 00:23:14.020 align:middle line:84%
Now that we have
propositions and predicates,

00:23:14.020 --> 00:23:17.140 align:middle line:84%
really useful thing is to
be able to combine them

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:19.870 align:middle line:84%
into bigger and more
complicated and new

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:22.110 align:middle line:90%
propositions and predicates.

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:23.850 align:middle line:84%
And we have a couple,
what are called.

00:23:23.850 --> 00:23:26.810 align:middle line:84%
Boolean operators,
that help us do that.

00:23:26.810 --> 00:23:37.070 align:middle line:84%
For example, if A and B are
propositions, propositions,

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:43.670 align:middle line:84%
we have what's called not A.
This is a new proposition.

00:23:43.670 --> 00:23:49.200 align:middle line:84%
It's sometimes written instead
as A with a bar on top.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:53.270 align:middle line:84%
It's sometimes also written
as that weird right angle

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:56.060 align:middle line:90%
symbol next to the A.

00:23:56.060 --> 00:23:57.630 align:middle line:90%
These all mean the same thing.

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:00.500 align:middle line:84%
They're just different
notations for the same thing.

00:24:00.500 --> 00:24:06.290 align:middle line:84%
And this is just the
proposition that A is false.

00:24:06.290 --> 00:24:09.590 align:middle line:90%
A is false.

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:13.290 align:middle line:84%
So you read it as not A.
And it means A is false.

00:24:13.290 --> 00:24:17.600 align:middle line:84%
We can clarify this with
what's called a truth table.

00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:20.360 align:middle line:84%
So here's A. And A
is a proposition,

00:24:20.360 --> 00:24:23.240 align:middle line:84%
which means there are really
only two possibilities.

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:25.840 align:middle line:90%
It's either true or it's false.

00:24:25.840 --> 00:24:28.850 align:middle line:84%
And so let's write down
both of those options.

00:24:28.850 --> 00:24:31.100 align:middle line:90%
It can be either true or false.

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And then we can look
at not A and ask,

00:24:35.140 --> 00:24:37.640 align:middle line:90%
what is not A when A is true?

00:24:37.640 --> 00:24:40.630 align:middle line:84%
Well not A is supposed to
flip it, so not A is false.

00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:44.800 align:middle line:84%
And when A is false,
not A is true.

00:24:44.800 --> 00:24:49.240 align:middle line:84%
So this truth table can
be taken as the definition

00:24:49.240 --> 00:24:59.030 align:middle line:90%
of not, so truth table.

00:24:59.030 --> 00:25:01.395 align:middle line:84%
And let's do some more
interesting truth tables.

00:25:01.395 --> 00:25:06.730 align:middle line:90%


00:25:06.730 --> 00:25:08.560 align:middle line:90%
Let's use two propositions now.

00:25:08.560 --> 00:25:16.256 align:middle line:84%
If we have A and B, well, then
there are four possibilities.

00:25:16.256 --> 00:25:20.960 align:middle line:90%


00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:22.770 align:middle line:90%
They might both be true.

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:25.520 align:middle line:84%
A might be true, and
B is false, or false

00:25:25.520 --> 00:25:26.970 align:middle line:90%
and true or false and false.

00:25:26.970 --> 00:25:29.610 align:middle line:84%
And our truth table is supposed
to cover all the possibilities.

00:25:29.610 --> 00:25:31.950 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to have
four rows this time.

00:25:31.950 --> 00:25:38.600 align:middle line:84%
And let's look at A and
B. This is a new operator.

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:41.120 align:middle line:84%
And it means what you think
it means because it's also

00:25:41.120 --> 00:25:41.840 align:middle line:90%
an English word.

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:45.740 align:middle line:84%
A and B means that both A and
B are supposed to be true.

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:51.290 align:middle line:84%
So if A and B are both
true, then A and B is true.

00:25:51.290 --> 00:25:53.185 align:middle line:90%
Otherwise, it's false.

00:25:53.185 --> 00:25:55.825 align:middle line:90%


00:25:55.825 --> 00:26:00.200 align:middle line:84%
A and B means both A
and B have to be true.

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:08.090 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, we have A or B, which
means at least one of A and B

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:09.950 align:middle line:90%
has to be true.

00:26:09.950 --> 00:26:12.470 align:middle line:84%
So if they're both
true, that's fine.

00:26:12.470 --> 00:26:15.630 align:middle line:90%
If only A is true, that's fine.

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:17.500 align:middle line:90%
If only B is true, that's fine.

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:22.920 align:middle line:84%
The only way for this to fail
is if both A and B are false.

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:27.310 align:middle line:84%
So I want to emphasize
this is an inclusive OR.

00:26:27.310 --> 00:26:29.560 align:middle line:84%
It's fine if both
of them are true.

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:34.800 align:middle line:84%
It just means that at least
one of them has to be true.

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:41.400 align:middle line:84%
Notation-wise, A and B
is also sometimes denoted

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:45.870 align:middle line:84%
A and this little
wedge symbol, B.

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:48.660 align:middle line:84%
You can remember it because that
looks kind of like a capital A

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:51.010 align:middle line:84%
for And, but you don't
put the cross in.

00:26:51.010 --> 00:26:53.110 align:middle line:84%
But honestly, if we're
looking for clarity,

00:26:53.110 --> 00:26:55.590 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a lot
clearer, especially

00:26:55.590 --> 00:27:01.350 align:middle line:84%
because A or B is also often
denoted with the same symbol

00:27:01.350 --> 00:27:02.490 align:middle line:90%
upside down.

00:27:02.490 --> 00:27:05.290 align:middle line:84%
And I don't have a clever
mnemonic for that one.

00:27:05.290 --> 00:27:08.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you're trying to
remember which one to use,

00:27:08.440 --> 00:27:09.700 align:middle line:90%
just use these.

00:27:09.700 --> 00:27:13.020 align:middle line:90%
That's my advice.

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:15.940 align:middle line:84%
But back to this OR, I said
this is an inclusive OR.

00:27:15.940 --> 00:27:19.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's totally fine if
A and B are both true.

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:23.387 align:middle line:84%
In English, that's not
always what we mean.

00:27:23.387 --> 00:27:28.810 align:middle line:84%
"And," "or," "not," these are
words in spoken English as well.

00:27:28.810 --> 00:27:30.710 align:middle line:84%
And when we're
talking about math,

00:27:30.710 --> 00:27:34.000 align:middle line:84%
when we're using these
words in a math formula,

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.120 align:middle line:84%
we mean exactly
what's written here.

00:27:37.120 --> 00:27:38.930 align:middle line:84%
But when we use these
words in English,

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:40.870 align:middle line:90%
we don't always mean that.

00:27:40.870 --> 00:27:44.440 align:middle line:84%
Spoken colloquial English
or other spoken languages

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:47.390 align:middle line:84%
are imprecise and
context-dependent.

00:27:47.390 --> 00:27:51.220 align:middle line:84%
And that really makes it
difficult to communicate

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:58.310 align:middle line:84%
precise things, especially
given the fact that as humans,

00:27:58.310 --> 00:28:00.950 align:middle line:84%
we communicate math
using spoken language.

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:03.100 align:middle line:84%
We're trying to
communicate precise things

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:06.680 align:middle line:84%
with an imprecise channel,
with an imprecise language.

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:10.810 align:middle line:84%
So as an example of
how bad this can get,

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:14.420 align:middle line:90%
let's look at this word "or."

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:17.270 align:middle line:90%
Say you're at a nice wedding.

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:19.650 align:middle line:84%
The waiter comes
around and says,

00:28:19.650 --> 00:28:23.620 align:middle line:84%
did you order the
chicken or the pasta?

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:27.200 align:middle line:90%


00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:28.920 align:middle line:84%
And when the waiter
asks this question,

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:32.506 align:middle line:84%
they're trying to communicate
some set of allowable responses.

00:28:32.506 --> 00:28:35.970 align:middle line:90%


00:28:35.970 --> 00:28:39.200 align:middle line:84%
So are you allowed to say,
I ordered the chicken, just

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.430 align:middle line:90%
the chicken?

00:28:40.430 --> 00:28:41.976 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, seems reasonable.

00:28:41.976 --> 00:28:45.770 align:middle line:90%


00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:49.400 align:middle line:84%
Pasta, you can say
I ordered the pasta.

00:28:49.400 --> 00:28:53.080 align:middle line:90%
Can you say I ordered both?

00:28:53.080 --> 00:28:56.150 align:middle line:90%


00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:58.910 align:middle line:90%
Probably not.

00:28:58.910 --> 00:29:03.150 align:middle line:84%
The catering company got all
the RSVP cards in advance.

00:29:03.150 --> 00:29:05.580 align:middle line:84%
And everyone was told
to pick just one.

00:29:05.580 --> 00:29:06.630 align:middle line:90%
So they did.

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:09.958 align:middle line:84%
So if you tell the waiter you
picked both, first of all,

00:29:09.958 --> 00:29:10.500 align:middle line:90%
you're lying.

00:29:10.500 --> 00:29:12.920 align:middle line:84%
Second of all, stop trying
to make their jobs harder.

00:29:12.920 --> 00:29:13.700 align:middle line:90%
It's hard enough.

00:29:13.700 --> 00:29:15.820 align:middle line:84%
They have hundreds
of people to serve.

00:29:15.820 --> 00:29:19.870 align:middle line:84%
So you're probably not
expected to say that one.

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:24.790 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, you're probably
not expected to say neither.

00:29:24.790 --> 00:29:26.990 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I could go back
and forth on that one.

00:29:26.990 --> 00:29:30.190 align:middle line:84%
But let's say everyone filled
out the RSVP card correctly,

00:29:30.190 --> 00:29:33.250 align:middle line:84%
and so the waiter isn't
expecting a Neither.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:37.540 align:middle line:84%
So here, chicken
or pasta, they were

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:39.530 align:middle line:84%
allowing this response
and this response,

00:29:39.530 --> 00:29:41.680 align:middle line:84%
but not these other
two responses.

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:45.610 align:middle line:84%
This is not how we defined
"or" in a math sense.

00:29:45.610 --> 00:29:48.340 align:middle line:84%
This is what's
called exclusive OR.

00:29:48.340 --> 00:29:50.210 align:middle line:84%
You have to pick
one or the other,

00:29:50.210 --> 00:29:52.570 align:middle line:90%
but not both and not neither.

00:29:52.570 --> 00:29:56.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is what
mathematicians would call XOR,

00:29:56.590 --> 00:30:00.170 align:middle line:90%
for exclusive OR.

00:30:00.170 --> 00:30:03.850 align:middle line:84%
So after dinner, the waiter
comes around again and says,

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:05.085 align:middle line:90%
you can have coffee or tea.

00:30:05.085 --> 00:30:09.580 align:middle line:90%


00:30:09.580 --> 00:30:10.540 align:middle line:90%
Excellent.

00:30:10.540 --> 00:30:13.220 align:middle line:84%
What responses are they
expecting this time?

00:30:13.220 --> 00:30:14.340 align:middle line:90%
Can you say just coffee?

00:30:14.340 --> 00:30:16.960 align:middle line:90%


00:30:16.960 --> 00:30:17.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:19.820 align:middle line:90%
Can you say, I want tea?

00:30:19.820 --> 00:30:22.420 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:25.540 align:middle line:90%
Can you say I want both?

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:28.400 align:middle line:84%
Waiter is going to look
at you side-eyed and say,

00:30:28.400 --> 00:30:31.040 align:middle line:84%
there's only one mug in front of
you, and I am not mixing them.

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:32.470 align:middle line:90%
This is a fancy venue.

00:30:32.470 --> 00:30:36.710 align:middle line:84%
So, no, they're probably not
expecting an answer of both.

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:37.880 align:middle line:90%
Can you say neither?

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:40.270 align:middle line:90%
I don't want coffee or tea.

00:30:40.270 --> 00:30:41.060 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's fine.

00:30:41.060 --> 00:30:42.500 align:middle line:90%
Not everyone wants a hot drink.

00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:44.500 align:middle line:84%
Even at a fancy restaurant,
not everyone wants--

00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:45.530 align:middle line:90%
a fancy wedding--

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:48.130 align:middle line:90%
I apologize.

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:52.160 align:middle line:84%
Not everyone wants a
hot drink after dinner.

00:30:52.160 --> 00:30:57.010 align:middle line:84%
So now you can ask for coffee
or tea or neither, but not both.

00:30:57.010 --> 00:31:00.035 align:middle line:84%
Surely, that's how we defined
OR in a math sense, right?

00:31:00.035 --> 00:31:02.890 align:middle line:90%


00:31:02.890 --> 00:31:05.200 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:31:05.200 --> 00:31:06.770 align:middle line:90%
These two are swapped.

00:31:06.770 --> 00:31:07.580 align:middle line:90%
This isn't OR.

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:10.590 align:middle line:84%
This is what
mathematicians call NAND.

00:31:10.590 --> 00:31:16.710 align:middle line:90%
It's the Not of the And, NAND.

00:31:16.710 --> 00:31:20.060 align:middle line:84%
Well, waiter used
the word "or" twice.

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:21.560 align:middle line:90%
Let's try one more.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:23.702 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they'll get
it right this time.

00:31:23.702 --> 00:31:26.410 align:middle line:84%
You ask for the coffee, and they
say you can have cream or sugar.

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:32.240 align:middle line:90%


00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:33.920 align:middle line:90%
Can you ask for cream?

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:36.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:31:36.830 --> 00:31:40.760 align:middle line:84%
Can you ask for
sugar, just sugar?

00:31:40.760 --> 00:31:42.020 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:44.600 align:middle line:90%
Can you ask for both?

00:31:44.600 --> 00:31:50.150 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, some people like a really
sweet and creamy drink, both.

00:31:50.150 --> 00:31:51.325 align:middle line:90%
Can you ask for neither?

00:31:51.325 --> 00:31:53.990 align:middle line:90%


00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:59.300 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, some people like black,
bitter coffee, inexplicably.

00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:02.220 align:middle line:84%
So all four of these
options are valid.

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:05.390 align:middle line:84%
This use of the word "or" also
doesn't mean what mathematicians

00:32:05.390 --> 00:32:07.320 align:middle line:90%
mean by the word "or."

00:32:07.320 --> 00:32:10.210 align:middle line:90%
This one means anything goes.

00:32:10.210 --> 00:32:12.240 align:middle line:84%
I'm just telling you
what your options are.

00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:14.736 align:middle line:84%
I don't have a
math term for that.

00:32:14.736 --> 00:32:15.690 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: True.

00:32:15.690 --> 00:32:18.180 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: True, yes.

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:21.270 align:middle line:84%
So three uses of the word
"or," none of them mean what

00:32:21.270 --> 00:32:23.640 align:middle line:90%
"or" means.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:25.890 align:middle line:90%
Isn't language fun?

00:32:25.890 --> 00:32:29.250 align:middle line:84%
The moral here is,
first of all, when

00:32:29.250 --> 00:32:32.370 align:middle line:84%
you see these in an actual
formula with other predicates

00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:35.760 align:middle line:84%
and quantifiers and whatnot,
we mean exactly what's

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:36.970 align:middle line:90%
written here.

00:32:36.970 --> 00:32:40.830 align:middle line:84%
If we use it in a
sentence, ideally, we also

00:32:40.830 --> 00:32:42.610 align:middle line:90%
mean what's written here.

00:32:42.610 --> 00:32:45.180 align:middle line:84%
But we might mess
up, as well, and slip

00:32:45.180 --> 00:32:47.740 align:middle line:84%
into colloquial,
context-dependent English.

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:51.330 align:middle line:84%
And if you're ever
confused, ask.

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:52.470 align:middle line:90%
If you're right, And.

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:55.710 align:middle line:84%
We messed up the wording,
we will thank you and fix it

00:32:55.710 --> 00:32:59.730 align:middle line:84%
if you're wrong, and
we meant what we wrote,

00:32:59.730 --> 00:33:01.470 align:middle line:84%
well, now you have
confidence that that

00:33:01.470 --> 00:33:03.270 align:middle line:90%
is what we meant to write.

00:33:03.270 --> 00:33:06.540 align:middle line:84%
And both parties are
happier because of it.

00:33:06.540 --> 00:33:08.330 align:middle line:84%
So please ask for
clarity if you're

00:33:08.330 --> 00:33:10.980 align:middle line:84%
ever unsure of the
wording we use,

00:33:10.980 --> 00:33:14.400 align:middle line:84%
whether it's these specific
words or anything else.

00:33:14.400 --> 00:33:17.090 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

00:33:17.090 --> 00:33:18.800 align:middle line:90%
Wonderful.

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:22.250 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at one
other operator.

00:33:22.250 --> 00:33:24.620 align:middle line:84%
We've looked at
AND and OR and NOT.

00:33:24.620 --> 00:33:28.197 align:middle line:84%
XOR and NAND, I
mean, they're there.

00:33:28.197 --> 00:33:29.370 align:middle line:90%
They're less important.

00:33:29.370 --> 00:33:31.470 align:middle line:84%
I would master
those three first.

00:33:31.470 --> 00:33:33.380 align:middle line:84%
I want to look at
one more that's

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:37.980 align:middle line:84%
really important, both for this
class and for proof writing.

00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:42.596 align:middle line:84%
And that is Implies,
implication.

00:33:42.596 --> 00:33:46.730 align:middle line:90%


00:33:46.730 --> 00:33:55.460 align:middle line:84%
We're going to write it
as A implies B. Sometimes,

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:59.570 align:middle line:84%
you'll see it written as A
arrow B or A double arrow

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:01.380 align:middle line:90%
B. There's no difference.

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:04.240 align:middle line:84%
These are all notations for
the same thing for this concept

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:05.000 align:middle line:90%
of implication.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.900 align:middle line:90%
A implies B

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:13.600 align:middle line:84%
And when read aloud, I recommend
reading it as A implies B,

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:24.790 align:middle line:84%
or equivalently, if A, then B.
If A, then B. This is already

00:34:24.790 --> 00:34:27.670 align:middle line:84%
starting to look like
a programming language.

00:34:27.670 --> 00:34:29.889 align:middle line:84%
And IF statements in
programming languages

00:34:29.889 --> 00:34:33.290 align:middle line:84%
are exactly doing what
implication in math is doing.

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:36.159 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk
about what that is.

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:39.489 align:middle line:84%
As before, we can figure
out what these terms mean

00:34:39.489 --> 00:34:42.190 align:middle line:90%
by drawing the truth table.

00:34:42.190 --> 00:34:52.130 align:middle line:84%
So we have A and B, true, true,
false, false, true, false, true,

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:53.540 align:middle line:90%
false.

00:34:53.540 --> 00:35:02.020 align:middle line:84%
A implies B. If A and B are
both true, does A imply B?

00:35:02.020 --> 00:35:04.730 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, seems pretty
intuitive, yeah.

00:35:04.730 --> 00:35:07.190 align:middle line:84%
If A and B are both
false, if false,

00:35:07.190 --> 00:35:10.185 align:middle line:84%
then false, again,
seems OK to me.

00:35:10.185 --> 00:35:13.220 align:middle line:90%


00:35:13.220 --> 00:35:18.490 align:middle line:84%
If A is true, and B is
false, if true, then false,

00:35:18.490 --> 00:35:21.010 align:middle line:90%
does that sound good to you?

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:24.780 align:middle line:84%
I saw a couple head shakes, a
couple nods, more head shakes,

00:35:24.780 --> 00:35:25.280 align:middle line:90%
though.

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:27.168 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, if true, then false.

00:35:27.168 --> 00:35:29.210 align:middle line:84%
That's kind of the whole
purpose of this wording.

00:35:29.210 --> 00:35:32.950 align:middle line:90%
If A is true, then B is true.

00:35:32.950 --> 00:35:35.720 align:middle line:84%
So if A is true, then
B better be true.

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:36.945 align:middle line:90%
And if it's false, we're sad.

00:35:36.945 --> 00:35:40.250 align:middle line:90%


00:35:40.250 --> 00:35:43.690 align:middle line:84%
Last case, if A is
false and B is true,

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:46.720 align:middle line:90%
should this be true or false?

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:49.420 align:middle line:90%
Think about it for a second.

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:51.280 align:middle line:90%
And let's take a poll.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:54.500 align:middle line:84%
Who thinks False Implies
True should be true?

00:35:54.500 --> 00:35:56.470 align:middle line:90%
Raise your hand.

00:35:56.470 --> 00:35:58.540 align:middle line:84%
Who thinks False
Implies True Should.

00:35:58.540 --> 00:35:59.240 align:middle line:90%
Be false?

00:35:59.240 --> 00:36:01.910 align:middle line:90%
Raise your hand.

00:36:01.910 --> 00:36:04.890 align:middle line:84%
Who just wants the answer and
doesn't want to think about it?

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:06.890 align:middle line:90%
Raise both hands.

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:10.310 align:middle line:90%
OK, the both hands win.

00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:13.190 align:middle line:90%
It was about an even split.

00:36:13.190 --> 00:36:19.170 align:middle line:84%
This answer is not so intuitive
in this abstract setting.

00:36:19.170 --> 00:36:22.530 align:middle line:84%
If A then B, well,
what does it mean?

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:24.650 align:middle line:90%
What do we want it to mean?

00:36:24.650 --> 00:36:26.610 align:middle line:90%
I claim, However, this--

00:36:26.610 --> 00:36:27.230 align:middle line:90%
what?

00:36:27.230 --> 00:36:30.460 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Last line.

00:36:30.460 --> 00:36:32.210 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Last
line-- oh, yeah, sorry.

00:36:32.210 --> 00:36:32.760 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:35.300 align:middle line:90%
This should be true.

00:36:35.300 --> 00:36:36.000 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.840 align:middle line:90%
See, I do make mistakes.

00:36:38.840 --> 00:36:42.590 align:middle line:84%
It's not so clear, but I claim
this is a task that you are all

00:36:42.590 --> 00:36:44.310 align:middle line:84%
familiar with in a
different context,

00:36:44.310 --> 00:36:45.930 align:middle line:90%
in many different contexts.

00:36:45.930 --> 00:36:47.880 align:middle line:90%
So let's make it concrete.

00:36:47.880 --> 00:36:49.700 align:middle line:90%
Let's pick an example.

00:36:49.700 --> 00:36:50.545 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:36:50.545 --> 00:36:59.970 align:middle line:90%


00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:03.330 align:middle line:90%
On Wednesdays, we wear pink.

00:37:03.330 --> 00:37:08.340 align:middle line:84%
Said differently, if it's
Wednesday, then wear pink.

00:37:08.340 --> 00:37:12.570 align:middle line:90%
Wednesday implies pink.

00:37:12.570 --> 00:37:16.590 align:middle line:90%
Wednesday implies pink.

00:37:16.590 --> 00:37:18.070 align:middle line:90%
Now it's an implication.

00:37:18.070 --> 00:37:20.590 align:middle line:84%
And let's go through the cases
and see what's happening.

00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:24.280 align:middle line:84%
So if it's Wednesday,
and I'm wearing pink,

00:37:24.280 --> 00:37:26.650 align:middle line:84%
am I obeying the
rule or violating it?

00:37:26.650 --> 00:37:28.420 align:middle line:90%
On Wednesdays we wear pink.

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:29.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I'm doing what it says.

00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:31.090 align:middle line:90%
On Wednesdays, we wear pink.

00:37:31.090 --> 00:37:31.870 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:37:31.870 --> 00:37:33.360 align:middle line:90%
So that one's fine.

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:38.050 align:middle line:84%
If it's Tuesday, and
I'm wearing that color,

00:37:38.050 --> 00:37:41.260 align:middle line:90%
whatever it is, and not pink--

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:46.110 align:middle line:84%
let's hide this- if
it's not Wednesday,

00:37:46.110 --> 00:37:49.410 align:middle line:84%
and I'm not wearing pink,
am I obeying the rule

00:37:49.410 --> 00:37:51.300 align:middle line:90%
or violating it?

00:37:51.300 --> 00:37:53.020 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I'm obeying that rule.

00:37:53.020 --> 00:37:54.450 align:middle line:90%
That's fine.

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:58.900 align:middle line:84%
If it's Wednesday,
and I'm wearing blue,

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:01.510 align:middle line:84%
am I obeying the
rule or violating it?

00:38:01.510 --> 00:38:02.480 align:middle line:90%
I'm violating it.

00:38:02.480 --> 00:38:03.947 align:middle line:90%
On Wednesdays, we wear pink.

00:38:03.947 --> 00:38:05.030 align:middle line:90%
I'm supposed to wear pink.

00:38:05.030 --> 00:38:08.170 align:middle line:84%
And if I'm not wearing
pink on a Wednesday,

00:38:08.170 --> 00:38:10.070 align:middle line:84%
I'm not doing what
the rule says.

00:38:10.070 --> 00:38:12.230 align:middle line:84%
And now we get to
the confusing case.

00:38:12.230 --> 00:38:19.630 align:middle line:84%
If it's Tuesday, not Wednesday,
and I am wearing pink,

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:21.720 align:middle line:84%
Am I obeying the
rule or violating it?

00:38:21.720 --> 00:38:25.930 align:middle line:90%


00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:28.420 align:middle line:90%
Thumbs up.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:30.880 align:middle line:90%
Anyone think I'm violating it?

00:38:30.880 --> 00:38:31.480 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:38:31.480 --> 00:38:33.980 align:middle line:84%
In this way, in this
concrete setting,

00:38:33.980 --> 00:38:37.060 align:middle line:84%
it makes total sense that
on Wednesdays we wear pink.

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:39.380 align:middle line:90%
On all other days, I don't care.

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:40.910 align:middle line:90%
Anything goes.

00:38:40.910 --> 00:38:44.980 align:middle line:84%
I only have an opinion on what
you're wearing on Wednesday.

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:48.410 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
define this to be true.

00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:51.640 align:middle line:90%
False implies true is true.

00:38:51.640 --> 00:38:54.800 align:middle line:84%
As I said, confusing
in an abstract setting

00:38:54.800 --> 00:38:56.660 align:middle line:84%
makes more sense if
you think about it

00:38:56.660 --> 00:38:59.660 align:middle line:90%
as obeying a certain rule.

00:38:59.660 --> 00:39:02.910 align:middle line:84%
If it's Wednesday, you have
to do something specific.

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:06.350 align:middle line:84%
If it's not Wednesday,
anything is fine.

00:39:06.350 --> 00:39:07.910 align:middle line:90%
Yes, question?

00:39:07.910 --> 00:39:10.610 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So with the example
of, say, if it's Wednesday,

00:39:10.610 --> 00:39:14.180 align:middle line:84%
and you're wearing--
you're violating the rule,

00:39:14.180 --> 00:39:19.850 align:middle line:84%
what if you're
wearing pink as well?

00:39:19.850 --> 00:39:21.330 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Yeah,
good question.

00:39:21.330 --> 00:39:23.370 align:middle line:84%
What if it's Wednesday,
and you're wearing blue?

00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:26.310 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we called
the true and false case.

00:39:26.310 --> 00:39:29.180 align:middle line:84%
But what if you're
wearing blue and pink?

00:39:29.180 --> 00:39:29.810 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:29.810 --> 00:39:33.120 align:middle line:84%
That was a less precise
phrasing on my part.

00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:36.110 align:middle line:84%
I should have said,
you're wearing only blue.

00:39:36.110 --> 00:39:38.850 align:middle line:84%
I assume if you're wearing
pink and some other colors,

00:39:38.850 --> 00:39:41.160 align:middle line:90%
I think that is OK here.

00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:41.730 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:39:41.730 --> 00:39:43.147 align:middle line:84%
I'd have to watch
the movie again.

00:39:43.147 --> 00:39:45.680 align:middle line:90%


00:39:45.680 --> 00:39:48.480 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, implication
is confusing.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:51.050 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk a little bit
more about implication.

00:39:51.050 --> 00:39:55.180 align:middle line:84%
In English, when
we say A implies B,

00:39:55.180 --> 00:39:58.580 align:middle line:84%
often there's a
connotation of causality.

00:39:58.580 --> 00:40:06.980 align:middle line:84%
A causes B. And often,
there's a connotation of time.

00:40:06.980 --> 00:40:12.040 align:middle line:84%
A happens, and then after
that, B happens because of A.

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:16.450 align:middle line:90%
So B is after is a consequence.

00:40:16.450 --> 00:40:20.210 align:middle line:84%
And neither of those
is what we mean.

00:40:20.210 --> 00:40:21.230 align:middle line:90%
There's no causality.

00:40:21.230 --> 00:40:24.340 align:middle line:90%
There's no time.

00:40:24.340 --> 00:40:28.420 align:middle line:84%
How do you put a time on
Goldbach's Conjecture.

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:30.040 align:middle line:90%
When it was conjecture maybe.

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:32.560 align:middle line:90%
But that's not what we mean.

00:40:32.560 --> 00:40:33.970 align:middle line:84%
When we say
Goldbach's Conjecture

00:40:33.970 --> 00:40:38.590 align:middle line:84%
implies that I'm wearing
pink on a Wednesday.

00:40:38.590 --> 00:40:42.280 align:middle line:84%
As mathematicians, when
we say the word "implies,"

00:40:42.280 --> 00:40:47.270 align:middle line:84%
we mean this truth table
and only this truth table.

00:40:47.270 --> 00:40:49.100 align:middle line:84%
There's no additional
connotation.

00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:50.025 align:middle line:90%
There's no causality.

00:40:50.025 --> 00:40:50.900 align:middle line:90%
There's nothing else.

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:54.710 align:middle line:90%
It's just this truth table.

00:40:54.710 --> 00:40:56.100 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:57.740 align:middle line:84%
It can be hard to
flip that switch

00:40:57.740 --> 00:40:59.270 align:middle line:84%
and redefine this
term that we're

00:40:59.270 --> 00:41:01.500 align:middle line:84%
familiar with from
somewhere else.

00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:03.390 align:middle line:84%
Because it does mean
something different now.

00:41:03.390 --> 00:41:05.120 align:middle line:90%
It means that.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:07.190 align:middle line:84%
And if you see
this in class, even

00:41:07.190 --> 00:41:09.050 align:middle line:84%
if it's written in
a paragraph, you

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:12.440 align:middle line:84%
should assume we
mean that first.

00:41:12.440 --> 00:41:13.770 align:middle line:90%
Was that your question?

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:14.870 align:middle line:90%
Please?

00:41:14.870 --> 00:41:16.228 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: So [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:16.228 --> 00:41:30.050 align:middle line:90%


00:41:30.050 --> 00:41:32.600 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: So
clarification on the concept

00:41:32.600 --> 00:41:36.080 align:middle line:84%
of time, if A then B, do we
need to know whether A is true

00:41:36.080 --> 00:41:40.430 align:middle line:90%
or not before we decide about B?

00:41:40.430 --> 00:41:42.260 align:middle line:84%
I would recommend
thinking about and B

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:44.400 align:middle line:90%
as two separate propositions.

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:46.380 align:middle line:84%
They each have their
own truth value.

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:47.730 align:middle line:90%
A is either true or false.

00:41:47.730 --> 00:41:49.570 align:middle line:90%
B is either true or false.

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:54.270 align:middle line:84%
We don't necessarily know what
they are, now or in the future.

00:41:54.270 --> 00:41:56.267 align:middle line:90%
But they're still propositions.

00:41:56.267 --> 00:41:58.350 align:middle line:84%
A might be the Goldbach
Conjecture, where we don't

00:41:58.350 --> 00:41:59.650 align:middle line:90%
know if it's true or false.

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:01.450 align:middle line:90%
But it's still a proposition.

00:42:01.450 --> 00:42:04.150 align:middle line:84%
It's still going to
be true or false.

00:42:04.150 --> 00:42:05.820 align:middle line:90%
We just don't know yet.

00:42:05.820 --> 00:42:09.150 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, we can always
combine propositions A and B

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:11.130 align:middle line:84%
into this bigger
proposition, if A,

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:16.170 align:middle line:84%
then B. A implies B. It's
just a new proposition where

00:42:16.170 --> 00:42:18.220 align:middle line:84%
once we know whether
A and B are true,

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:21.870 align:middle line:84%
we'll know whether the
implication is true.

00:42:21.870 --> 00:42:23.410 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:23.910 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:42:23.910 --> 00:42:26.950 align:middle line:90%


00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:28.290 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:35.610 align:middle line:84%
So another example
of implication,

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:41.130 align:middle line:84%
you might be familiar
with less than 3.

00:42:41.130 --> 00:42:46.140 align:middle line:84%
This is a preemoji
heart, means I love you.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:46.890 align:middle line:90%
Got some chuckles.

00:42:46.890 --> 00:42:48.400 align:middle line:90%
I don't know why.

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:51.430 align:middle line:90%
I'm showing my age maybe.

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:53.120 align:middle line:90%
So less than 3 means I love you.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:59.350 align:middle line:84%
What I have seen, I have
seen occasionally less than 4

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:02.390 align:middle line:84%
as an intensifier,
like I really love you.

00:43:02.390 --> 00:43:06.550 align:middle line:84%
I love you more than
3, I love you 4.

00:43:06.550 --> 00:43:08.560 align:middle line:90%
And this irks me.

00:43:08.560 --> 00:43:13.630 align:middle line:84%
I hate this, not because
I'm against love,

00:43:13.630 --> 00:43:17.380 align:middle line:84%
but because this is the
stronger mathematical statement.

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:20.120 align:middle line:90%
Less than 3 implies less than 4.

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:23.380 align:middle line:84%
If we know x is less than
3, some number x, well,

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:26.200 align:middle line:84%
then we know that
x is less than 4.

00:43:26.200 --> 00:43:28.670 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, we know more
information than that.

00:43:28.670 --> 00:43:31.120 align:middle line:90%
We know it's not pi.

00:43:31.120 --> 00:43:32.620 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:43:32.620 --> 00:43:35.030 align:middle line:90%
So this implies that.

00:43:35.030 --> 00:43:37.310 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
stronger statement.

00:43:37.310 --> 00:43:38.570 align:middle line:90%
So you've weakened it.

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:39.920 align:middle line:90%
You love me less.

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:41.590 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:41.590 --> 00:43:44.420 align:middle line:84%
It should be less
than 2, or something.

00:43:44.420 --> 00:43:46.710 align:middle line:84%
But only mathematicians
would get that.

00:43:46.710 --> 00:43:49.700 align:middle line:84%
So I don't actually recommend
sending that to your Valentine.

00:43:49.700 --> 00:43:53.720 align:middle line:90%
But that's always bothered me.

00:43:53.720 --> 00:43:56.330 align:middle line:84%
Let's do one other
quick example.

00:43:56.330 --> 00:44:00.290 align:middle line:84%
Who's familiar with Descartes,
I think, therefore I am?

00:44:00.290 --> 00:44:03.500 align:middle line:90%
Excellent.

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:07.340 align:middle line:90%
So, I think, therefore I am.

00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:11.690 align:middle line:90%
I think, therefore I am.

00:44:11.690 --> 00:44:14.580 align:middle line:84%
And this one has
two claims to it.

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:17.900 align:middle line:84%
It's not only saying that
thinking implies am-ing.

00:44:17.900 --> 00:44:20.900 align:middle line:84%
But it's also
saying that I think.

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:27.860 align:middle line:84%
So it's asserting that T
is true, and T implies am.

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:28.490 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:44:28.490 --> 00:44:30.110 align:middle line:90%
So that's Descartes.

00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:33.290 align:middle line:84%
What I have seen that
bothers me is a shirt

00:44:33.290 --> 00:44:34.680 align:middle line:90%
and a pillow and a meme.

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:36.360 align:middle line:84%
And you can go off
and buy all of this.

00:44:36.360 --> 00:44:38.630 align:middle line:84%
I don't recommend
giving it money.

00:44:38.630 --> 00:44:43.860 align:middle line:84%
"I do not think, therefore I do
not am," which I find hilarious,

00:44:43.860 --> 00:44:46.050 align:middle line:90%
but also frustrating.

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:54.450 align:middle line:84%
So "I do not think"
implies "I do not am."

00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:56.100 align:middle line:84%
So it's also claiming
I don't think.

00:44:56.100 --> 00:44:57.810 align:middle line:90%
I don't have an opinion on that.

00:44:57.810 --> 00:45:00.190 align:middle line:84%
But it's saying
this implication,

00:45:00.190 --> 00:45:03.390 align:middle line:84%
not thinking
implies, not aiming.

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:06.100 align:middle line:84%
And it irks me because
that's not equivalent.

00:45:06.100 --> 00:45:09.390 align:middle line:84%
It's not equivalent
to Descartes.

00:45:09.390 --> 00:45:13.530 align:middle line:84%
Let's go out on a limb
here, and let's assume--

00:45:13.530 --> 00:45:14.490 align:middle line:90%
big ask, I know.

00:45:14.490 --> 00:45:18.240 align:middle line:84%
Let's assume that my shoe
doesn't think, my right shoe

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:20.250 align:middle line:90%
specifically.

00:45:20.250 --> 00:45:23.760 align:middle line:84%
But it still exists,
let's assume.

00:45:23.760 --> 00:45:25.950 align:middle line:90%
If my shoe thinks and doesn't--

00:45:25.950 --> 00:45:28.270 align:middle line:84%
sorry, doesn't think,
but still exists,

00:45:28.270 --> 00:45:30.540 align:middle line:90%
Descartes is fine with that.

00:45:30.540 --> 00:45:33.720 align:middle line:90%
False implies true is fine.

00:45:33.720 --> 00:45:35.710 align:middle line:90%
But the meme isn't.

00:45:35.710 --> 00:45:38.680 align:middle line:84%
Not thinking is supposed
to imply not am-ing.

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:42.340 align:middle line:84%
But my shoe ams even
if it doesn't think .

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:45.640 align:middle line:84%
So these two statements
are not equivalent.

00:45:45.640 --> 00:45:47.240 align:middle line:90%
It should be, I do not am.

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:48.640 align:middle line:90%
Therefore, I do not think.

00:45:48.640 --> 00:45:51.310 align:middle line:90%
Which gets zero hits on Google.

00:45:51.310 --> 00:45:52.540 align:middle line:90%
We need to fix this.

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:54.235 align:middle line:90%
Question?

00:45:54.235 --> 00:45:55.735 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Looking
at the truth table,

00:45:55.735 --> 00:46:00.010 align:middle line:84%
right implementation
has certain [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:00.010 --> 00:46:01.940 align:middle line:90%


00:46:01.940 --> 00:46:02.740 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Ooh.

00:46:02.740 --> 00:46:04.880 align:middle line:84%
All right, that's
a great comment.

00:46:04.880 --> 00:46:05.800 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:07.065 align:middle line:90%
Let's go back to the front.

00:46:07.065 --> 00:46:10.390 align:middle line:90%


00:46:10.390 --> 00:46:12.730 align:middle line:84%
What your colleague
suggested was

00:46:12.730 --> 00:46:19.870 align:middle line:84%
we can write A implies B by
combining the earlier operators.

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:21.010 align:middle line:90%
Oops.

00:46:21.010 --> 00:46:24.510 align:middle line:90%
A implies B is equivalent to--

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:29.530 align:middle line:90%


00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:31.690 align:middle line:84%
and can you remind
me what you said?

00:46:31.690 --> 00:46:34.840 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: It was B
or NOT A and NOT B.

00:46:34.840 --> 00:46:43.650 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: OK, B
or Not A and Not B--

00:46:43.650 --> 00:46:46.980 align:middle line:84%
and the claim is that this
is equivalent to A implies B,

00:46:46.980 --> 00:46:50.830 align:middle line:84%
has the same truth table
as A implies B. In fact,

00:46:50.830 --> 00:46:53.410 align:middle line:84%
if you check it, we can
simplify it even further.

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:58.380 align:middle line:84%
We don't need this
extra clause on B. B

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:06.810 align:middle line:84%
or not A. This is
equivalent to A implies B.

00:47:06.810 --> 00:47:08.910 align:middle line:84%
What this is really saying
is that the only way

00:47:08.910 --> 00:47:12.870 align:middle line:84%
to violate this, the only
way to violate A implies B,

00:47:12.870 --> 00:47:15.660 align:middle line:84%
is for A to be true
and B to be false.

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:21.000 align:middle line:84%
And so if either of these
is true, then you're fine.

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:23.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, absolutely,
there are relationships

00:47:23.190 --> 00:47:27.750 align:middle line:84%
between these operators,
really nice observation.

00:47:27.750 --> 00:47:30.750 align:middle line:84%
But going back to Descartes
for just a second,

00:47:30.750 --> 00:47:35.490 align:middle line:84%
we looked at a
implies B and we also

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:40.250 align:middle line:84%
looked at not a implies B.
Let's look at some others.

00:47:40.250 --> 00:47:48.190 align:middle line:84%
B implies A. Not B implies Not
A. If this is our statement,

00:47:48.190 --> 00:47:50.836 align:middle line:84%
A implies B, if we
flip them around,

00:47:50.836 --> 00:47:52.503 align:middle line:84%
B implies A, that's
called the converse.

00:47:52.503 --> 00:47:55.510 align:middle line:90%


00:47:55.510 --> 00:47:58.570 align:middle line:84%
That's the converse of
the original statement.

00:47:58.570 --> 00:48:01.670 align:middle line:84%
And this one here,
Not B implies Not A,

00:48:01.670 --> 00:48:03.516 align:middle line:84%
that's what's called
the contrapositive.

00:48:03.516 --> 00:48:09.370 align:middle line:90%


00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And the one we saw
over there with Not A

00:48:12.490 --> 00:48:18.070 align:middle line:84%
implies Not B, that's
called the inverse.

00:48:18.070 --> 00:48:20.390 align:middle line:84%
You don't really need to
know all of these terms.

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:21.932 align:middle line:84%
It's just nice to
know they're there.

00:48:21.932 --> 00:48:28.360 align:middle line:84%
Because A implies B is
equivalent to one of these two.

00:48:28.360 --> 00:48:31.660 align:middle line:90%
And it's not the nice one.

00:48:31.660 --> 00:48:34.400 align:middle line:84%
A implies B is equivalent
to its contrapositive.

00:48:34.400 --> 00:48:38.880 align:middle line:84%
Not B implies not A
Wednesday implies pink.

00:48:38.880 --> 00:48:43.670 align:middle line:84%
So if you're not wearing pink,
it better not be Wednesday.

00:48:43.670 --> 00:48:48.380 align:middle line:84%
A implies B. Not B implies Not
A. So these two are equivalent.

00:48:48.380 --> 00:48:50.570 align:middle line:84%
And also, the converse
and the inverse

00:48:50.570 --> 00:48:52.070 align:middle line:84%
are equivalent for
the same reason.

00:48:52.070 --> 00:48:56.120 align:middle line:84%
They're contrapositives
of each other.

00:48:56.120 --> 00:49:00.620 align:middle line:84%
So that Descartes meme was using
the inverse, when they probably

00:49:00.620 --> 00:49:03.830 align:middle line:84%
meant to use the
contrapositive, I assume,

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:07.880 align:middle line:84%
because I assume they
thought that deeply about it.

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:10.620 align:middle line:84%
That is everything I wanted
to say about implication.

00:49:10.620 --> 00:49:12.985 align:middle line:84%
Does anyone have more
questions before we move on?

00:49:12.985 --> 00:49:16.250 align:middle line:90%


00:49:16.250 --> 00:49:16.990 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:23.180 align:middle line:90%


00:49:23.180 --> 00:49:27.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, very briefly, I've
mentioned sets a few times.

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:30.830 align:middle line:84%
And I've used set
notation a few times.

00:49:30.830 --> 00:49:33.890 align:middle line:84%
So let's go ahead and
make that more precise.

00:49:33.890 --> 00:49:36.280 align:middle line:84%
Because we're going to be
talking about sets all term,

00:49:36.280 --> 00:49:39.850 align:middle line:84%
I just want us to have that
common language to fall back on.

00:49:39.850 --> 00:49:48.043 align:middle line:84%
So a set is a
collection of objects.

00:49:48.043 --> 00:49:55.140 align:middle line:90%


00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:58.330 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to be
more precise than this.

00:49:58.330 --> 00:50:01.350 align:middle line:84%
If you want to dig
into set theory,

00:50:01.350 --> 00:50:03.310 align:middle line:84%
into the foundations
of mathematics,

00:50:03.310 --> 00:50:04.450 align:middle line:90%
it's really interesting.

00:50:04.450 --> 00:50:05.500 align:middle line:90%
There's a lot of stuff there.

00:50:05.500 --> 00:50:07.458 align:middle line:84%
But that's not what we're
doing in this course.

00:50:07.458 --> 00:50:09.080 align:middle line:84%
A set is a collection
of objects.

00:50:09.080 --> 00:50:11.790 align:middle line:90%


00:50:11.790 --> 00:50:13.480 align:middle line:90%
Let me give lots of examples.

00:50:13.480 --> 00:50:17.950 align:middle line:84%
An example is the set that
contains 6, 1, 2, and 0.

00:50:17.950 --> 00:50:20.790 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to write
sets with these curly braces.

00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:25.740 align:middle line:84%
Crucially, when we're
talking about a set,

00:50:25.740 --> 00:50:27.125 align:middle line:90%
the order doesn't matter.

00:50:27.125 --> 00:50:33.570 align:middle line:90%


00:50:33.570 --> 00:50:35.475 align:middle line:84%
And there's no such
thing as a repeat.

00:50:35.475 --> 00:50:38.680 align:middle line:90%


00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:42.460 align:middle line:84%
All I care about is, which
things are in your set and which

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:43.430 align:middle line:90%
ones aren't?

00:50:43.430 --> 00:50:51.100 align:middle line:84%
So this set is
exactly equal to 2160

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:53.350 align:middle line:84%
because they have the
same four elements.

00:50:53.350 --> 00:50:57.310 align:middle line:90%
This set is exactly equal to 6--

00:50:57.310 --> 00:51:01.340 align:middle line:90%
yeah, 6, 1, 2, 0, 0.

00:51:01.340 --> 00:51:03.920 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of weird to
write 0 in there twice,

00:51:03.920 --> 00:51:05.750 align:middle line:90%
but technically, it's OK.

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:08.050 align:middle line:90%
I don't recommend doing that.

00:51:08.050 --> 00:51:12.680 align:middle line:84%
But this has the four
numbers 0, 1, 2, and 6 in it.

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:16.900 align:middle line:84%
And so these other sets,
they're exactly the same set.

00:51:16.900 --> 00:51:20.290 align:middle line:84%
We already saw, N, the
natural numbers, this

00:51:20.290 --> 00:51:25.035 align:middle line:84%
is the set 0, 1, 2, 3,
and so on, all the way up.

00:51:25.035 --> 00:51:28.210 align:middle line:90%


00:51:28.210 --> 00:51:31.120 align:middle line:90%
We also have the set--

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:35.210 align:middle line:84%
that's a Blackboard
bold z, which

00:51:35.210 --> 00:51:39.800 align:middle line:84%
includes the integers, natural
numbers, and their negatives, 1

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:48.080 align:middle line:84%
and minus 1 and 2 and minus 2,
and so on, all the integers,

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:50.150 align:middle line:90%
integers.

00:51:50.150 --> 00:51:57.290 align:middle line:84%
A couple more useful ones, we
have Q is the set of rationals,

00:51:57.290 --> 00:51:59.990 align:middle line:84%
so fractions you can get
by dividing some integer

00:51:59.990 --> 00:52:02.390 align:middle line:90%
by some non-zero integer.

00:52:02.390 --> 00:52:05.540 align:middle line:90%
We have the real numbers.

00:52:05.540 --> 00:52:09.830 align:middle line:84%
That's a bold R.
Blackboard bold R.

00:52:09.830 --> 00:52:17.283 align:middle line:84%
And we also have C, the complex
numbers, complex numbers.

00:52:17.283 --> 00:52:21.230 align:middle line:90%


00:52:21.230 --> 00:52:26.720 align:middle line:84%
So those are five sets that we
will very frequently talk about.

00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:28.910 align:middle line:84%
Let's give some more
examples of sets.

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:34.710 align:middle line:90%
There's the empty set, Which?

00:52:34.710 --> 00:52:38.560 align:middle line:84%
Is written as a circle
with a through it.

00:52:38.560 --> 00:52:41.880 align:middle line:84%
It's also sometimes written
as an open curly brace

00:52:41.880 --> 00:52:46.230 align:middle line:84%
and a closed curly brace
with nothing inside.

00:52:46.230 --> 00:52:47.853 align:middle line:90%
These two mean the same thing.

00:52:47.853 --> 00:52:50.020 align:middle line:84%
They're just different
notations for the same thing.

00:52:50.020 --> 00:52:53.520 align:middle line:84%
The empty set is a set
that contains nothing.

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:54.550 align:middle line:90%
It is a set.

00:52:54.550 --> 00:52:55.300 align:middle line:90%
It is a thing.

00:52:55.300 --> 00:52:56.140 align:middle line:90%
It does exist.

00:52:56.140 --> 00:52:57.910 align:middle line:90%
It just has zero elements.

00:52:57.910 --> 00:53:00.670 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, this set over
here has four elements.

00:53:00.670 --> 00:53:03.820 align:middle line:84%
This set over here has
infinitely many elements.

00:53:03.820 --> 00:53:06.870 align:middle line:84%
These other sets have infinitely
many elements as well.

00:53:06.870 --> 00:53:09.762 align:middle line:90%
But is it the same infinity?

00:53:09.762 --> 00:53:11.890 align:middle line:90%
No, not always.

00:53:11.890 --> 00:53:13.120 align:middle line:90%
And that's a confusing thing.

00:53:13.120 --> 00:53:16.050 align:middle line:90%
Come ask me if you're curious.

00:53:16.050 --> 00:53:19.750 align:middle line:84%
Let's see, one other set I
wanted to give an example of.

00:53:19.750 --> 00:53:24.210 align:middle line:84%
Let's call this one A, just
so we have a name for it.

00:53:24.210 --> 00:53:26.148 align:middle line:90%
Let's define B is--

00:53:26.148 --> 00:53:27.190 align:middle line:90%
what did I want to write?

00:53:27.190 --> 00:53:34.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, 2, 3, 4, and empty. set.

00:53:34.240 --> 00:53:37.510 align:middle line:90%
B is a set with three elements.

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:40.130 align:middle line:84%
It has the number
2 as an element.

00:53:40.130 --> 00:53:42.350 align:middle line:90%
It has this set as an element.

00:53:42.350 --> 00:53:45.760 align:middle line:84%
And it has the empty
set as an element.

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:53.590 align:middle line:84%
Is 3 an element of / We
would write this as 3

00:53:53.590 --> 00:53:57.920 align:middle line:84%
is an element of B. There's
that notation again.

00:53:57.920 --> 00:53:59.830 align:middle line:90%
Is three an element of B?

00:53:59.830 --> 00:54:02.900 align:middle line:84%
No it's inside one
of the elements of B,

00:54:02.900 --> 00:54:08.620 align:middle line:84%
but it's not one of the
elements itself, so no.

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:10.840 align:middle line:90%
So we have this notation.

00:54:10.840 --> 00:54:12.350 align:middle line:90%
Oh no, I just used that.

00:54:12.350 --> 00:54:15.250 align:middle line:90%
Let's move over here.

00:54:15.250 --> 00:54:17.170 align:middle line:90%
Eraser, help.

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:20.200 align:middle line:90%
Found it.

00:54:20.200 --> 00:54:23.170 align:middle line:84%
We have this notion of
being an element a set

00:54:23.170 --> 00:54:26.560 align:middle line:84%
that we have already
talked about a few times.

00:54:26.560 --> 00:54:30.730 align:middle line:84%
You can also ask a set to
be a subset of another one.

00:54:30.730 --> 00:54:44.730 align:middle line:84%
So x in A means x is
an element of A. A

00:54:44.730 --> 00:54:48.420 align:middle line:84%
and then this new symbol--
this is a sideways-- or this

00:54:48.420 --> 00:54:52.410 align:middle line:84%
is a curly C with a
line underneath it.

00:54:52.410 --> 00:55:03.390 align:middle line:84%
A is a subset or equal to B.
A is a subset or equal to B.

00:55:03.390 --> 00:55:05.100 align:middle line:90%
Note the similarity of two A's.

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:07.710 align:middle line:84%
Less than or equal
to B, less equal

00:55:07.710 --> 00:55:10.090 align:middle line:84%
doesn't really make sense
for sets, but this one does.

00:55:10.090 --> 00:55:14.640 align:middle line:84%
Subset means everything
that's in A is also in B.

00:55:14.640 --> 00:55:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And B might contain
more besides.

00:55:17.910 --> 00:55:23.370 align:middle line:84%
For example, the set
that contains 2 and 1,

00:55:23.370 --> 00:55:27.010 align:middle line:90%
is that a subset of A?

00:55:27.010 --> 00:55:30.250 align:middle line:90%
A was over there.

00:55:30.250 --> 00:55:34.040 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, everything that's
in here is also in here--

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:34.935 align:middle line:90%
totally fine.

00:55:34.935 --> 00:55:38.860 align:middle line:90%


00:55:38.860 --> 00:55:39.560 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:55:39.560 --> 00:55:43.875 align:middle line:90%
Is the empty set a subset of A?

00:55:43.875 --> 00:55:56.930 align:middle line:90%


00:55:56.930 --> 00:55:57.430 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:55:57.430 --> 00:55:59.720 align:middle line:90%
All right, I got some thumbs up.

00:55:59.720 --> 00:56:01.210 align:middle line:90%
I got no thumbs down.

00:56:01.210 --> 00:56:03.140 align:middle line:90%
I got a lot of blank faces.

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:04.610 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to assume
that means Yes.

00:56:04.610 --> 00:56:08.440 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, everything that's an
element of the empty set

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:12.500 align:middle line:84%
should also be an element of A.
Well, it's kind of weird, right?

00:56:12.500 --> 00:56:15.075 align:middle line:84%
Because there are no
elements of the empty set.

00:56:15.075 --> 00:56:18.910 align:middle line:84%
And we can't really
check this rule

00:56:18.910 --> 00:56:21.100 align:middle line:90%
for any elements of the left.

00:56:21.100 --> 00:56:23.770 align:middle line:84%
So it kind of feels like
this shouldn't be true,

00:56:23.770 --> 00:56:26.270 align:middle line:84%
because there's
nothing to instantiate.

00:56:26.270 --> 00:56:29.480 align:middle line:84%
There are no elements
here to talk about.

00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:34.850 align:middle line:84%
But a better way to think
of it is prove me wrong.

00:56:34.850 --> 00:56:36.560 align:middle line:84%
Show me an element
on the left that

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:38.250 align:middle line:90%
isn't an element on the right.

00:56:38.250 --> 00:56:40.730 align:middle line:90%
You can't.

00:56:40.730 --> 00:56:43.310 align:middle line:84%
You can't violate the rule,
and therefore, the rule

00:56:43.310 --> 00:56:44.086 align:middle line:90%
is satisfied.

00:56:44.086 --> 00:56:47.810 align:middle line:90%


00:56:47.810 --> 00:56:51.240 align:middle line:84%
A little bit confusing, but when
you look at it the right way,

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:54.470 align:middle line:90%
hopefully it makes sense.

00:56:54.470 --> 00:56:59.240 align:middle line:84%
Just like we were able to
combine propositions- A and B,

00:56:59.240 --> 00:57:00.740 align:middle line:90%
A or B--

00:57:00.740 --> 00:57:02.840 align:middle line:90%
we can combine sets.

00:57:02.840 --> 00:57:06.170 align:middle line:90%
We can look at A union B--

00:57:06.170 --> 00:57:09.890 align:middle line:90%
this is the union--

00:57:09.890 --> 00:57:15.680 align:middle line:84%
which is the set of elements
that are in A or B or both.

00:57:15.680 --> 00:57:20.090 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, A
union B for our example,

00:57:20.090 --> 00:57:23.820 align:middle line:84%
it certainly includes
6 and 1 and 2 and 0.

00:57:23.820 --> 00:57:25.978 align:middle line:84%
And also-- well,
it already has 2,

00:57:25.978 --> 00:57:27.520 align:middle line:84%
so we don't need to
write that again.

00:57:27.520 --> 00:57:34.110 align:middle line:84%
And it has the set 3, 4, and it
has the empty set, so everything

00:57:34.110 --> 00:57:36.840 align:middle line:90%
in A or B or both.

00:57:36.840 --> 00:57:38.880 align:middle line:84%
And remember, I don't
have to say, the Or Both

00:57:38.880 --> 00:57:43.240 align:middle line:84%
because OR is
inclusive by default.

00:57:43.240 --> 00:57:47.010 align:middle line:84%
We can likewise
do a intersect B,

00:57:47.010 --> 00:57:52.376 align:middle line:84%
which is the elements that are
in both, so the intersection.

00:57:52.376 --> 00:57:55.410 align:middle line:90%


00:57:55.410 --> 00:58:01.330 align:middle line:84%
In this case, A intersect B is--
well, what's in both A and B?

00:58:01.330 --> 00:58:03.000 align:middle line:90%
I think it's just the two.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:05.590 align:middle line:84%
There's a 2 in both, and
nothing else is in common.

00:58:05.590 --> 00:58:09.720 align:middle line:84%
So that's going to be
just the set containing 2.

00:58:09.720 --> 00:58:14.460 align:middle line:84%
There's also the set
difference, A minus B,

00:58:14.460 --> 00:58:19.920 align:middle line:84%
sometimes written
as A backslash B.

00:58:19.920 --> 00:58:21.436 align:middle line:90%
And that's the set difference.

00:58:21.436 --> 00:58:25.720 align:middle line:90%


00:58:25.720 --> 00:58:29.110 align:middle line:84%
It's the things in
A that aren't in B.

00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:31.090 align:middle line:84%
So it's A, but take
away everything

00:58:31.090 --> 00:58:33.880 align:middle line:84%
in B. So in this
case, it's going

00:58:33.880 --> 00:58:40.330 align:middle line:84%
to equal 6 and 1 and not the
two, but we still keep the 0.

00:58:40.330 --> 00:58:41.740 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:58:41.740 --> 00:58:45.010 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: So that set is--

00:58:45.010 --> 00:58:49.540 align:middle line:84%
we basically [INAUDIBLE] the
subset of everything, right?

00:58:49.540 --> 00:58:50.440 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Yep.

00:58:50.440 --> 00:58:55.973 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So [INAUDIBLE] also
both in A and B and [INAUDIBLE]?

00:58:55.973 --> 00:58:57.140 align:middle line:90%
Zachary Abel: Good question.

00:58:57.140 --> 00:58:58.900 align:middle line:84%
So the question
was, we've already

00:58:58.900 --> 00:59:02.650 align:middle line:84%
said that the empty set
is a subset of everything.

00:59:02.650 --> 00:59:05.890 align:middle line:84%
So shouldn't it
be in both A and B

00:59:05.890 --> 00:59:09.400 align:middle line:84%
and therefore, in
their intersection?

00:59:09.400 --> 00:59:11.770 align:middle line:90%
Really good question.

00:59:11.770 --> 00:59:15.490 align:middle line:84%
And the difference is that we
have two different meanings

00:59:15.490 --> 00:59:17.290 align:middle line:90%
of "in."

00:59:17.290 --> 00:59:20.820 align:middle line:84%
We said that the empty set
is a subset of everything,

00:59:20.820 --> 00:59:23.270 align:middle line:84%
but not an element
of everything.

00:59:23.270 --> 00:59:25.730 align:middle line:84%
So the empty set
is an element of B

00:59:25.730 --> 00:59:28.160 align:middle line:84%
because it was written
as one of the elements.

00:59:28.160 --> 00:59:30.740 align:middle line:84%
But it's not an element
of A, because these

00:59:30.740 --> 00:59:33.410 align:middle line:84%
are all four elements of A.
There's nothing else in there.

00:59:33.410 --> 00:59:35.040 align:middle line:90%
So A is a subset--

00:59:35.040 --> 00:59:39.630 align:middle line:84%
sorry, the empty set is a
subset of A and a subset of B.

00:59:39.630 --> 00:59:43.400 align:middle line:90%
But it's not an element of both.

00:59:43.400 --> 00:59:44.340 align:middle line:90%
Great question.

00:59:44.340 --> 00:59:45.330 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for asking.

00:59:45.330 --> 00:59:45.920 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:59:45.920 --> 00:59:49.880 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Why does A have two
zeros if there's no repeats?

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:53.160 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Why can A have
two zeros if there's no repeats?

00:59:53.160 --> 00:59:54.830 align:middle line:90%
Good question.

00:59:54.830 --> 00:59:58.520 align:middle line:84%
It's because it doesn't
actually have two zeros.

00:59:58.520 --> 01:00:00.750 align:middle line:90%
I just wrote the two zeros.

01:00:00.750 --> 01:00:03.210 align:middle line:84%
Each of them says, 0 is
an element of this set.

01:00:03.210 --> 01:00:04.430 align:middle line:90%
By the way, did you forget?

01:00:04.430 --> 01:00:07.070 align:middle line:90%
0 is an element of the set.

01:00:07.070 --> 01:00:08.280 align:middle line:90%
So it doesn't have two.

01:00:08.280 --> 01:00:11.720 align:middle line:84%
There's no way for it
to remember it has two.

01:00:11.720 --> 01:00:14.400 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes, in
some weird cases,

01:00:14.400 --> 01:00:17.460 align:middle line:84%
it might make sense to write a
set where the same element is

01:00:17.460 --> 01:00:19.920 align:middle line:90%
written twice.

01:00:19.920 --> 01:00:21.935 align:middle line:90%
And so there's that example.

01:00:21.935 --> 01:00:27.540 align:middle line:90%


01:00:27.540 --> 01:00:28.840 align:middle line:90%
Yes, question?

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:30.656 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Can you
have A [INAUDIBLE]?

01:00:30.656 --> 01:00:36.887 align:middle line:90%


01:00:36.887 --> 01:00:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: That's
a great question.

01:00:38.470 --> 01:00:43.110 align:middle line:84%
So if A also had
a 3 and 4 in it--

01:00:43.110 --> 01:00:46.450 align:middle line:84%
so let's pretend this
also has a 3 and 4 in it.

01:00:46.450 --> 01:00:50.430 align:middle line:84%
And then we ask about
A minus B. We take away

01:00:50.430 --> 01:00:52.740 align:middle line:84%
from A everything
that's in B, everything

01:00:52.740 --> 01:00:54.840 align:middle line:90%
that's an element of B.

01:00:54.840 --> 01:00:58.810 align:middle line:84%
So would we be
removing the 3 and 4?

01:00:58.810 --> 01:01:03.900 align:middle line:84%
So if we have a 6 and 1 and
a 2 and a 0 and a 3 and 4,

01:01:03.900 --> 01:01:07.500 align:middle line:84%
and we subtract the
set-- what was it?

01:01:07.500 --> 01:01:12.930 align:middle line:90%
2 and 3, 4, and empty set.

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:16.650 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is no, the
3 and 4 don't go away.

01:01:16.650 --> 01:01:20.460 align:middle line:84%
Because we want to take all
the elements of the first set

01:01:20.460 --> 01:01:23.610 align:middle line:84%
that are not elements
of the second set.

01:01:23.610 --> 01:01:26.230 align:middle line:84%
And 3 and 4 are not
elements of the second set.

01:01:26.230 --> 01:01:29.370 align:middle line:90%
They're nested too deep.

01:01:29.370 --> 01:01:31.630 align:middle line:90%
3 Is not an element of this set.

01:01:31.630 --> 01:01:35.910 align:middle line:84%
This whole set is an
element of this set.

01:01:35.910 --> 01:01:36.820 align:middle line:90%
Make sense?

01:01:36.820 --> 01:01:37.360 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:01:37.360 --> 01:01:42.120 align:middle line:84%
So this difference would keep
the 6 and the 1, not the 2,

01:01:42.120 --> 01:01:46.830 align:middle line:84%
would keep the 0 and keep
the 3 and keep the 4.

01:01:46.830 --> 01:01:49.030 align:middle line:90%
Awesome.

01:01:49.030 --> 01:01:52.290 align:middle line:90%
Similar to sets, we have--

01:01:52.290 --> 01:01:56.760 align:middle line:84%
oh, sorry, before that,
one of the reasons I'm

01:01:56.760 --> 01:01:59.910 align:middle line:84%
talking about sets right now,
beyond the fact that we need

01:01:59.910 --> 01:02:03.870 align:middle line:84%
to talk about sets,
is the fact that sets

01:02:03.870 --> 01:02:08.500 align:middle line:84%
and propositions and predicates
are very closely related.

01:02:08.500 --> 01:02:10.535 align:middle line:84%
And they can both be
useful for the other.

01:02:10.535 --> 01:02:14.040 align:middle line:90%


01:02:14.040 --> 01:02:17.473 align:middle line:84%
Specifically, I want to talk
about set builder notation.

01:02:17.473 --> 01:02:29.490 align:middle line:90%


01:02:29.490 --> 01:02:32.170 align:middle line:84%
And that is where
you take a set,

01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:38.400 align:middle line:84%
and you describe a subset
a set by using a predicate.

01:02:38.400 --> 01:02:43.110 align:middle line:84%
So for example, we can
look at the set of all n

01:02:43.110 --> 01:02:47.465 align:middle line:84%
in the natural numbers
such that n is prime.

01:02:47.465 --> 01:02:54.840 align:middle line:90%


01:02:54.840 --> 01:02:58.410 align:middle line:84%
So we have this predicate
of n over here on the right.

01:02:58.410 --> 01:03:00.660 align:middle line:84%
And we're pulling out
all of the elements

01:03:00.660 --> 01:03:02.980 align:middle line:84%
of this set, the
natural numbers,

01:03:02.980 --> 01:03:06.420 align:middle line:84%
but only the ones that
satisfy our predicate.

01:03:06.420 --> 01:03:08.380 align:middle line:90%
So this is set builder notation.

01:03:08.380 --> 01:03:11.970 align:middle line:84%
You have elements a set
such that this predicate

01:03:11.970 --> 01:03:13.100 align:middle line:90%
is satisfied.

01:03:13.100 --> 01:03:15.430 align:middle line:90%
This is the notation we'll use.

01:03:15.430 --> 01:03:20.350 align:middle line:84%
And this set, of course, will
return the set of primes--

01:03:20.350 --> 01:03:27.300 align:middle line:84%
2, 3, 5, 7, not 9,
globe, 11, and so on.

01:03:27.300 --> 01:03:30.910 align:middle line:90%


01:03:30.910 --> 01:03:34.700 align:middle line:84%
Very useful, we're going
to use that all the time.

01:03:34.700 --> 01:03:36.810 align:middle line:90%
Similar to sets, we have tuples.

01:03:36.810 --> 01:03:39.970 align:middle line:90%


01:03:39.970 --> 01:03:42.543 align:middle line:84%
This is an ordered
list of elements.

01:03:42.543 --> 01:03:49.480 align:middle line:90%


01:03:49.480 --> 01:03:50.955 align:middle line:90%
And repeats are OK.

01:03:50.955 --> 01:03:54.610 align:middle line:90%


01:03:54.610 --> 01:03:56.440 align:middle line:84%
And it's written
with parentheses

01:03:56.440 --> 01:03:57.453 align:middle line:90%
instead of curly braces.

01:03:57.453 --> 01:04:07.270 align:middle line:90%


01:04:07.270 --> 01:04:13.880 align:middle line:84%
For example, the
tuple 6, 1, 2, 0

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:17.210 align:middle line:84%
is a sequence with
four elements.

01:04:17.210 --> 01:04:23.120 align:middle line:84%
This is not the same
as 6, 1, 2, 0, 0, which

01:04:23.120 --> 01:04:26.330 align:middle line:90%
is a tuple with five elements.

01:04:26.330 --> 01:04:27.780 align:middle line:90%
As sets, they're the same.

01:04:27.780 --> 01:04:29.220 align:middle line:90%
They have the same elements.

01:04:29.220 --> 01:04:31.880 align:middle line:90%
But this one has repeats.

01:04:31.880 --> 01:04:33.230 align:middle line:90%
So they're different.

01:04:33.230 --> 01:04:39.553 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, neither of these
is equivalent to 2, 1, 6, 0.

01:04:39.553 --> 01:04:41.720 align:middle line:84%
Because the order is
different, even if the elements

01:04:41.720 --> 01:04:42.750 align:middle line:90%
are the same.

01:04:42.750 --> 01:04:46.550 align:middle line:84%
So a tuple cares
about the order.

01:04:46.550 --> 01:04:51.500 align:middle line:84%
By the way, last I checked 2.160
is identification, estimation,

01:04:51.500 --> 01:04:55.230 align:middle line:84%
and learning in
MechE, not the same,

01:04:55.230 --> 01:04:58.558 align:middle line:84%
even though they
have the same digits.

01:04:58.558 --> 01:05:00.650 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't really
make sense to ask

01:05:00.650 --> 01:05:02.300 align:middle line:84%
for the intersection
or the union

01:05:02.300 --> 01:05:05.390 align:middle line:90%
or the difference of tuples.

01:05:05.390 --> 01:05:08.060 align:middle line:90%
So we're not even going to try.

01:05:08.060 --> 01:05:12.030 align:middle line:84%
Any questions about
sets or tuples?

01:05:12.030 --> 01:05:14.740 align:middle line:90%
Nice.

01:05:14.740 --> 01:05:19.070 align:middle line:84%
Let's go back to the definition
I probably deleted already.

01:05:19.070 --> 01:05:21.750 align:middle line:90%


01:05:21.750 --> 01:05:24.720 align:middle line:84%
A proof is a verification
of a proposition

01:05:24.720 --> 01:05:28.170 align:middle line:84%
by a sequence of logical
deductions from a base

01:05:28.170 --> 01:05:29.770 align:middle line:90%
set of axioms.

01:05:29.770 --> 01:05:31.240 align:middle line:90%
I hope I got that right.

01:05:31.240 --> 01:05:33.990 align:middle line:84%
We've already talked at
length about propositions,

01:05:33.990 --> 01:05:36.210 align:middle line:90%
one of those three terms.

01:05:36.210 --> 01:05:40.260 align:middle line:84%
Let's turn to the
next one, axioms.

01:05:40.260 --> 01:05:42.845 align:middle line:84%
We've used both of those
boards, on to this board.

01:05:42.845 --> 01:05:53.410 align:middle line:90%


01:05:53.410 --> 01:05:53.910 align:middle line:90%
Nice.

01:05:53.910 --> 01:05:57.720 align:middle line:90%


01:05:57.720 --> 01:06:14.940 align:middle line:84%
And axiom is a proposition
we assume is true.

01:06:14.940 --> 01:06:18.580 align:middle line:90%


01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:21.257 align:middle line:84%
You might have
heard, when you're

01:06:21.257 --> 01:06:23.840 align:middle line:84%
doing mathematical proofs, you
shouldn't be assuming anything.

01:06:23.840 --> 01:06:25.540 align:middle line:90%
You have to prove everything.

01:06:25.540 --> 01:06:27.170 align:middle line:90%
And that's not quite true.

01:06:27.170 --> 01:06:28.550 align:middle line:90%
We need somewhere to start.

01:06:28.550 --> 01:06:32.620 align:middle line:84%
We need some foundation
to build up from.

01:06:32.620 --> 01:06:35.780 align:middle line:84%
The trick is to declare
all of them in advance.

01:06:35.780 --> 01:06:38.050 align:middle line:90%
These are the axioms I'm using.

01:06:38.050 --> 01:06:43.270 align:middle line:84%
And if you assume these
axioms, then these proofs

01:06:43.270 --> 01:06:46.420 align:middle line:84%
tell you other things
that also have to be true.

01:06:46.420 --> 01:06:49.130 align:middle line:84%
So the axioms are the
things you start with.

01:06:49.130 --> 01:06:51.080 align:middle line:90%
We take them to be true.

01:06:51.080 --> 01:06:53.840 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, people say we
take them to be self-evident.

01:06:53.840 --> 01:06:55.690 align:middle line:90%
But I don't like that phrasing.

01:06:55.690 --> 01:07:03.380 align:middle line:84%
Because they're not necessarily
true in some holistic sense.

01:07:03.380 --> 01:07:05.380 align:middle line:84%
We just assume them to
be true for the sake

01:07:05.380 --> 01:07:07.520 align:middle line:90%
of the math we're doing now.

01:07:07.520 --> 01:07:09.980 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, you can
often have axioms

01:07:09.980 --> 01:07:12.830 align:middle line:84%
that contradict each other,
as long as you're not

01:07:12.830 --> 01:07:15.230 align:middle line:90%
using them at the same time.

01:07:15.230 --> 01:07:18.780 align:middle line:90%
For example, let's see.

01:07:18.780 --> 01:07:32.090 align:middle line:84%
For example, we have the famous
Euclid's parallel postulate.

01:07:32.090 --> 01:07:35.670 align:middle line:84%
So Euclid, in 200 BC, or
whenever he was alive,

01:07:35.670 --> 01:07:39.050 align:middle line:84%
maybe 2000-- someone
can tell me--

01:07:39.050 --> 01:07:42.390 align:middle line:84%
wrote a book, The Elements,
Euclid's Elements,

01:07:42.390 --> 01:07:45.150 align:middle line:84%
that chronicled all
of Euclidean geometry.

01:07:45.150 --> 01:07:47.130 align:middle line:84%
That's why it's called
Euclidean geometry.

01:07:47.130 --> 01:07:49.910 align:middle line:84%
He literally wrote
the book on it.

01:07:49.910 --> 01:07:53.460 align:middle line:84%
And at the beginning of the
book, he had five axioms.

01:07:53.460 --> 01:07:56.820 align:middle line:84%
"Postulate" is another word
for "axiom," a little outdated,

01:07:56.820 --> 01:07:59.360 align:middle line:90%
but still there.

01:07:59.360 --> 01:08:03.260 align:middle line:84%
And parallel postulate, the
fifth of the five axioms,

01:08:03.260 --> 01:08:07.120 align:middle line:84%
famously for centuries,
millennia, people

01:08:07.120 --> 01:08:09.820 align:middle line:84%
kept trying to prove that
actually, the parallel postulate

01:08:09.820 --> 01:08:11.540 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have to be an axiom.

01:08:11.540 --> 01:08:14.890 align:middle line:84%
You can prove it's true if
you only assume the first four

01:08:14.890 --> 01:08:16.479 align:middle line:90%
axioms.

01:08:16.479 --> 01:08:18.140 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't have
to be an axiom.

01:08:18.140 --> 01:08:19.750 align:middle line:90%
It can be a theorem.

01:08:19.750 --> 01:08:22.279 align:middle line:84%
And people kept trying and
kept trying and kept trying.

01:08:22.279 --> 01:08:24.880 align:middle line:84%
By the way, the statement
of the parallel postulate

01:08:24.880 --> 01:08:33.880 align:middle line:84%
is that for every
point p and line

01:08:33.880 --> 01:08:41.439 align:middle line:84%
l that doesn't
contain p, p not in l,

01:08:41.439 --> 01:08:59.740 align:middle line:84%
there exists a unique line l
prime through p parallel to l.

01:08:59.740 --> 01:09:03.710 align:middle line:84%
In picture, if you have a
point here and some line that

01:09:03.710 --> 01:09:06.859 align:middle line:84%
doesn't go through that
point, then there's

01:09:06.859 --> 01:09:11.279 align:middle line:84%
a unique line parallel and
going through your point.

01:09:11.279 --> 01:09:11.930 align:middle line:90%
Here's p.

01:09:11.930 --> 01:09:13.520 align:middle line:90%
Here's l.

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:14.760 align:middle line:90%
Intuitive, right?

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:16.670 align:middle line:90%
Makes sense.

01:09:16.670 --> 01:09:21.109 align:middle line:84%
And Euclid took this as
an axiom and went with it.

01:09:21.109 --> 01:09:25.229 align:middle line:84%
But can we prove this, based
on the other four axioms?

01:09:25.229 --> 01:09:27.140 align:middle line:84%
And turns out,
thousands of years

01:09:27.140 --> 01:09:29.569 align:middle line:84%
later, we finally
know the answer.

01:09:29.569 --> 01:09:31.160 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:09:31.160 --> 01:09:32.270 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:09:32.270 --> 01:09:33.569 align:middle line:90%
This is not a theorem.

01:09:33.569 --> 01:09:36.229 align:middle line:84%
It does not follow from
the other four axioms.

01:09:36.229 --> 01:09:43.370 align:middle line:84%
Because we know what happens
if you change the axiom.

01:09:43.370 --> 01:09:46.370 align:middle line:84%
Things do happen in
a meaningful way.

01:09:46.370 --> 01:09:49.250 align:middle line:84%
For example, instead
of saying there

01:09:49.250 --> 01:09:57.080 align:middle line:84%
is a unique line, a unique line,
let's change that to no lines.

01:09:57.080 --> 01:10:01.110 align:middle line:84%
There are no lines through your
point parallel to your line.

01:10:01.110 --> 01:10:03.090 align:middle line:84%
The concept of
parallel lines doesn't

01:10:03.090 --> 01:10:08.640 align:middle line:84%
exist if we use that axiom
instead of Euclid's version

01:10:08.640 --> 01:10:13.470 align:middle line:84%
and the other four
axioms that Euclid did,

01:10:13.470 --> 01:10:14.873 align:middle line:90%
you can get spherical geometry.

01:10:14.873 --> 01:10:19.650 align:middle line:90%


01:10:19.650 --> 01:10:25.890 align:middle line:84%
In spherical geometry,
your plane, your canvas,

01:10:25.890 --> 01:10:28.560 align:middle line:90%
is a sphere instead of a plane.

01:10:28.560 --> 01:10:32.220 align:middle line:90%
A line is a great circle.

01:10:32.220 --> 01:10:36.000 align:middle line:84%
It's a circle whose center
is the center of the sphere.

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:39.450 align:middle line:84%
And a point isn't just a
point, but it's a point,

01:10:39.450 --> 01:10:44.460 align:middle line:84%
and it's antipode, the one
directly across from it

01:10:44.460 --> 01:10:45.780 align:middle line:90%
on the sphere.

01:10:45.780 --> 01:10:49.200 align:middle line:84%
And if that's how we
define points and lines,

01:10:49.200 --> 01:10:50.800 align:middle line:84%
then there are no
parallel lines.

01:10:50.800 --> 01:10:54.570 align:middle line:84%
All great circles
intersect each other.

01:10:54.570 --> 01:10:57.900 align:middle line:84%
And we get a meaningful geometry
that we can prove stuff with,

01:10:57.900 --> 01:11:02.800 align:middle line:84%
that we can prove different
things with than Euclid could.

01:11:02.800 --> 01:11:04.820 align:middle line:84%
Since we have a
different set of axioms,

01:11:04.820 --> 01:11:07.040 align:middle line:84%
we're going to have a
different set of conclusions.

01:11:07.040 --> 01:11:09.910 align:middle line:90%
But it's still meaningful.

01:11:09.910 --> 01:11:13.250 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, if we replace
this-- instead of no lines,

01:11:13.250 --> 01:11:19.285 align:middle line:84%
we do infinitely
many lines, well,

01:11:19.285 --> 01:11:21.410 align:middle line:84%
there's another version of
geometry that does that.

01:11:21.410 --> 01:11:32.570 align:middle line:84%
It's hyperbolic geometry,
lots of ways to draw it.

01:11:32.570 --> 01:11:34.820 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes, it's
drawn in a circle.

01:11:34.820 --> 01:11:40.120 align:middle line:84%
But now a line is a
part of a circle that's

01:11:40.120 --> 01:11:42.370 align:middle line:90%
perpendicular to the boundary.

01:11:42.370 --> 01:11:45.040 align:middle line:90%
A point is just a point.

01:11:45.040 --> 01:11:48.500 align:middle line:84%
But now if we have a line
and a point not on that line,

01:11:48.500 --> 01:11:51.440 align:middle line:84%
well, parallel just means
they don't intersect.

01:11:51.440 --> 01:11:57.740 align:middle line:84%
So, well, here is a line through
p that doesn't intersect l.

01:11:57.740 --> 01:12:01.220 align:middle line:90%
Well, here's another one.

01:12:01.220 --> 01:12:02.670 align:middle line:90%
And here's another one.

01:12:02.670 --> 01:12:05.720 align:middle line:84%
There are lots of them,
infinitely many lines through p

01:12:05.720 --> 01:12:06.985 align:middle line:90%
that don't touch l.

01:12:06.985 --> 01:12:09.950 align:middle line:90%


01:12:09.950 --> 01:12:12.290 align:middle line:84%
And so this is a
different kind of geometry

01:12:12.290 --> 01:12:16.640 align:middle line:84%
that satisfies a
different set of axioms.

01:12:16.640 --> 01:12:19.370 align:middle line:84%
And so no, you can't prove the
fifth axiom from the first four.

01:12:19.370 --> 01:12:21.950 align:middle line:84%
Because you can change the fifth
one and get new conclusions

01:12:21.950 --> 01:12:24.655 align:middle line:84%
that make sense and
aren't contradictory.

01:12:24.655 --> 01:12:26.030 align:middle line:84%
Now, I've said a
couple of times,

01:12:26.030 --> 01:12:31.730 align:middle line:84%
we can change it and get
a new system of geometry.

01:12:31.730 --> 01:12:34.610 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can imagine
you can always

01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:38.060 align:middle line:84%
change your axioms to some
other set of assumptions

01:12:38.060 --> 01:12:42.350 align:middle line:84%
and make a mathematical
theory out of it.

01:12:42.350 --> 01:12:45.530 align:middle line:84%
Does any set of
assumptions work?

01:12:45.530 --> 01:12:48.410 align:middle line:84%
Are they all as
good as the others?

01:12:48.410 --> 01:12:52.230 align:middle line:84%
Well, there are a couple of
things that can go wrong.

01:12:52.230 --> 01:12:54.890 align:middle line:84%
There are a couple of
properties you might want

01:12:54.890 --> 01:12:56.513 align:middle line:90%
your set of axioms to satisfy.

01:12:56.513 --> 01:13:04.620 align:middle line:90%


01:13:04.620 --> 01:13:19.410 align:middle line:84%
A set of axioms is
consistent when you

01:13:19.410 --> 01:13:29.280 align:middle line:90%
can't prove that false is true.

01:13:29.280 --> 01:13:32.220 align:middle line:90%
And we need that, right?

01:13:32.220 --> 01:13:34.890 align:middle line:84%
Let me see if that's
how we defined it.

01:13:34.890 --> 01:13:38.730 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, if no proposition can
be proved and disproved,

01:13:38.730 --> 01:13:42.570 align:middle line:84%
we need true and false
to be different things.

01:13:42.570 --> 01:13:46.000 align:middle line:84%
Because remember, false
implies anything you want.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:48.190 align:middle line:84%
That's sometimes called
the principle of explosion,

01:13:48.190 --> 01:13:49.570 align:middle line:90%
by the way, great name.

01:13:49.570 --> 01:13:51.160 align:middle line:90%
False implies anything.

01:13:51.160 --> 01:13:55.520 align:middle line:84%
So if false is true, and
false implies anything,

01:13:55.520 --> 01:13:58.870 align:middle line:90%
then everything is true.

01:13:58.870 --> 01:14:01.840 align:middle line:84%
So we don't want
to be able to prove

01:14:01.840 --> 01:14:05.710 align:middle line:84%
that false is true, because then
our theory is uninteresting.

01:14:05.710 --> 01:14:08.780 align:middle line:84%
Because everything is true,
and everything is false.

01:14:08.780 --> 01:14:13.420 align:middle line:84%
So we definitely want a set
of axioms that is consistent.

01:14:13.420 --> 01:14:17.770 align:middle line:84%
Ideally, we would also
have a set of axioms--

01:14:17.770 --> 01:14:28.780 align:middle line:84%
a set of axioms is
complete when every true--

01:14:28.780 --> 01:14:32.620 align:middle line:84%
let's see, yeah,
every true proposition

01:14:32.620 --> 01:14:40.980 align:middle line:90%
can be proved from the axioms.

01:14:40.980 --> 01:14:46.030 align:middle line:90%


01:14:46.030 --> 01:14:48.770 align:middle line:84%
We want things to
be true or false.

01:14:48.770 --> 01:14:51.370 align:middle line:84%
And we want proof
to be the metric

01:14:51.370 --> 01:14:53.880 align:middle line:84%
by which we decide whether
something is true or false.

01:14:53.880 --> 01:14:56.840 align:middle line:84%
If we can find a proof
for it, it's true.

01:14:56.840 --> 01:14:58.490 align:middle line:84%
Ideally, if it's
not true, we'd be

01:14:58.490 --> 01:15:00.800 align:middle line:84%
able to find a proof
for the opposite,

01:15:00.800 --> 01:15:03.350 align:middle line:90%
for the not of that proposition.

01:15:03.350 --> 01:15:06.500 align:middle line:84%
So the baseline
things, the two things

01:15:06.500 --> 01:15:08.870 align:middle line:84%
you would want in
a set of axioms

01:15:08.870 --> 01:15:11.820 align:middle line:84%
that is nice to work with, you
would want it to be consistent.

01:15:11.820 --> 01:15:14.600 align:middle line:84%
You would want it
to be complete.

01:15:14.600 --> 01:15:19.700 align:middle line:84%
And then Kurt Godel comes along
and says, nope, can't have both.

01:15:19.700 --> 01:15:23.450 align:middle line:84%
There's what's called the
Godel Incompleteness Theorem.

01:15:23.450 --> 01:15:29.540 align:middle line:84%
That's G-O-umlaut-D-E-L. Godel
was able to prove that you

01:15:29.540 --> 01:15:32.810 align:middle line:84%
can't have a system of axioms
that is both consistent

01:15:32.810 --> 01:15:38.420 align:middle line:84%
and complete, as long as it's
complicated enough to just do

01:15:38.420 --> 01:15:43.040 align:middle line:84%
arithmetic, addition
and multiplication.

01:15:43.040 --> 01:15:46.580 align:middle line:90%
You can't have both.

01:15:46.580 --> 01:15:48.890 align:middle line:84%
We certainly want to be
able to add and multiply

01:15:48.890 --> 01:15:52.900 align:middle line:84%
numbers, which means we
have to pick consistency

01:15:52.900 --> 01:15:54.230 align:middle line:90%
or completeness.

01:15:54.230 --> 01:15:56.330 align:middle line:84%
And I know which
one I'm picking.

01:15:56.330 --> 01:15:59.800 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to pick consistent,
so that true and false

01:15:59.800 --> 01:16:01.090 align:middle line:90%
have meaning.

01:16:01.090 --> 01:16:05.770 align:middle line:84%
What this means-- and
this kind of messes

01:16:05.770 --> 01:16:07.840 align:middle line:90%
with my head a little bit.

01:16:07.840 --> 01:16:09.820 align:middle line:84%
What Gödel's
completeness theorem--

01:16:09.820 --> 01:16:13.750 align:middle line:84%
sorry, Incompleteness Theorem
tells us is that there are true

01:16:13.750 --> 01:16:17.350 align:middle line:84%
statements in math, in whatever
set of axioms we're working

01:16:17.350 --> 01:16:22.325 align:middle line:84%
with, there are true statements
that cannot be proved.

01:16:22.325 --> 01:16:24.200 align:middle line:84%
You're never going to
be able to disprove it.

01:16:24.200 --> 01:16:28.240 align:middle line:84%
But if you want to prove it,
you have to add more axioms.

01:16:28.240 --> 01:16:30.200 align:middle line:84%
But then once you
add more axioms,

01:16:30.200 --> 01:16:33.430 align:middle line:84%
that bigger set of axioms
now has other true statements

01:16:33.430 --> 01:16:37.300 align:middle line:84%
that can't be proved
with those axioms.

01:16:37.300 --> 01:16:41.920 align:middle line:84%
So conceivably, we might ask you
to prove a problem in homework

01:16:41.920 --> 01:16:45.800 align:middle line:84%
that can't be proved from the
axioms, even though it's true.

01:16:45.800 --> 01:16:47.180 align:middle line:90%
We're not going to do that.

01:16:47.180 --> 01:16:48.530 align:middle line:90%
That's mean.

01:16:48.530 --> 01:16:51.050 align:middle line:84%
Conceivably,
Goldbach's Conjecture

01:16:51.050 --> 01:16:54.410 align:middle line:90%
might be true, but unprovable.

01:16:54.410 --> 01:16:56.930 align:middle line:90%
Maybe, I don't know.

01:16:56.930 --> 01:16:59.270 align:middle line:90%
Question?

01:16:59.270 --> 01:17:00.410 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

01:17:00.410 --> 01:17:03.230 align:middle line:90%


01:17:03.230 --> 01:17:04.860 align:middle line:84%
Zachary Abel: Yeah,
excellent question.

01:17:04.860 --> 01:17:08.990 align:middle line:84%
If something doesn't have a
proof, how do we know it's true?

01:17:08.990 --> 01:17:10.680 align:middle line:90%
That is a really good question.

01:17:10.680 --> 01:17:14.120 align:middle line:84%
And that's also getting back
into the set theory and logic

01:17:14.120 --> 01:17:16.280 align:middle line:84%
and underpinnings
of math that are too

01:17:16.280 --> 01:17:18.230 align:middle line:90%
in the weeds for this course.

01:17:18.230 --> 01:17:22.070 align:middle line:84%
But I'm happy to discuss
it afterward if you'd like.

01:17:22.070 --> 01:17:24.950 align:middle line:84%
Last thing I want
to say about axioms.

01:17:24.950 --> 01:17:27.530 align:middle line:84%
Every mathematician
needs a set of axioms

01:17:27.530 --> 01:17:29.150 align:middle line:84%
that they're
working with so they

01:17:29.150 --> 01:17:30.890 align:middle line:84%
know what they're
allowed to assume

01:17:30.890 --> 01:17:34.790 align:middle line:90%
as they're proving new things.

01:17:34.790 --> 01:17:38.930 align:middle line:84%
What axioms are we going
to use in this class?

01:17:38.930 --> 01:17:42.950 align:middle line:84%
Roughly speaking, all
of high school math.

01:17:42.950 --> 01:17:46.610 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that any
fact that you think

01:17:46.610 --> 01:17:50.940 align:middle line:84%
is general enough and familiar
enough and simple enough

01:17:50.940 --> 01:17:53.340 align:middle line:84%
to be included in basically,
every high school math

01:17:53.340 --> 01:17:54.460 align:middle line:90%
curriculum.

01:17:54.460 --> 01:17:58.110 align:middle line:84%
You're allowed to assume
it, and go from there.

01:17:58.110 --> 01:18:00.850 align:middle line:84%
Ideally, we ask
you to identify it.

01:18:00.850 --> 01:18:03.700 align:middle line:90%
Write down fact.

01:18:03.700 --> 01:18:05.085 align:middle line:84%
Write the theorem
you're stating,

01:18:05.085 --> 01:18:06.990 align:middle line:84%
or the theorem you're
assuming, like,

01:18:06.990 --> 01:18:10.710 align:middle line:84%
the product of two
even numbers is even.

01:18:10.710 --> 01:18:12.370 align:middle line:90%
I know this from high school.

01:18:12.370 --> 01:18:14.220 align:middle line:90%
And then go ahead and use it.

01:18:14.220 --> 01:18:17.040 align:middle line:84%
Because ideally, at
every step in a proof,

01:18:17.040 --> 01:18:20.680 align:middle line:90%
we know why each thing is true.

01:18:20.680 --> 01:18:23.320 align:middle line:84%
And if sometimes the
reason is that's an axiom,

01:18:23.320 --> 01:18:25.385 align:middle line:84%
I'm assuming it,
we should say that.

01:18:25.385 --> 01:18:28.350 align:middle line:90%


01:18:28.350 --> 01:18:31.890 align:middle line:90%
Are there any questions?

01:18:31.890 --> 01:18:33.490 align:middle line:90%
All right, that's all I've got.

01:18:33.490 --> 01:18:35.760 align:middle line:84%
Be sure to go to
recitation tomorrow.

01:18:35.760 --> 01:18:37.720 align:middle line:84%
You can check your
time on Canvas.

01:18:37.720 --> 01:18:39.580 align:middle line:84%
You can switch your
time on Canvas.

01:18:39.580 --> 01:18:41.230 align:middle line:84%
We look forward to
seeing you then.

01:18:41.230 --> 01:18:43.250 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much.

01:18:43.250 --> 01:18:47.000 align:middle line:90%